# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: algebraic-geometry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The fundamental objects of study in algebraic geometry are algebraic varieties, which are geometric manifestations of solutions of systems of polynomial equations.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Examples of the most studied classes of algebraic varieties are lines, circles, parabolas, ellipses, hyperbolas, cubic curves like elliptic curves, and quartic curves like lemniscates and Cassini ovals.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] A point of the plane lies on an algebraic curve if its coordinates satisfy a given polynomial equation.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Basic questions involve the study of points of special interest like singular points, inflection points and points at infinity.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] More advanced questions involve the topology of the curve and the relationship between curves defined by different equations.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Algebraic geometry occupies a central place in modern mathematics and has multiple conceptual connections with such diverse fields as complex analysis, topology and number theory.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] As a study of systems of polynomial equations in several variables, the subject of algebraic geometry begins with finding specific solutions via equation solving, and then proceeds to understand the intrinsic properties of the totality of solutions of a system of equations.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This understanding requires both conceptual theory and computational technique.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] In the 20th century, algebraic geometry split into several subareas.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] One key achievement of this abstract algebraic geometry is Grothendieck's scheme theory which allows one to use sheaf theory to study algebraic varieties in a way which is very similar to its use in the study of differential and analytic manifolds.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This is obtained by extending the notion of point: In classical algebraic geometry, a point of an affine variety may be identified, through Hilbert's Nullstellensatz, with a maximal ideal of the coordinate ring, while the points of the corresponding affine scheme are all prime ideals of this ring.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This means that a point of such a scheme may be either a usual point or a sub-variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This approach also enables a unification of the language and the tools of classical algebraic geometry, mainly concerned with complex points, and of algebraic number theory.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Wiles' proof of the longstanding conjecture called Fermat's Last Theorem is an example of the power of this approach.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] In classical algebraic geometry, the main objects of interest are the vanishing sets of collections of polynomials, meaning the set of all points that simultaneously satisfy one or more polynomial equations.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] In classical algebraic geometry, this field was always the complex numbers **C**, but many of the same results are true if we assume only that *k* is algebraically closed.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] We consider the affine space of dimension *n* over *k*, denoted **A**n(*k*) (or more simply **A***n*, when *k* is clear from the context).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] When one fixes a coordinate system, one may identify **A**n(*k*) with *k**n*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The purpose of not working with *k**n* is to emphasize that one "forgets" the vector space structure that *k*n carries.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The property of a function to be polynomial (or regular) does not depend on the choice of a coordinate system in **A***n*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] When a coordinate system is chosen, the regular functions on the affine *n*-space may be identified with the ring of polynomial functions in *n* variables over *k*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Therefore, the set of the regular functions on **A***n* is a ring, which is denoted *k*[**A***n*].
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] We say that a polynomial *vanishes* at a point if evaluating it at that point gives zero.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Let *S* be a set of polynomials in *k*[**A**n].
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The *vanishing set of S* (or *vanishing locus* or *zero set*) is the set *V*(*S*) of all points in **A***n* where every polynomial in *S* vanishes.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] A subset of **A***n* which is *V*(*S*), for some *S*, is called an *algebraic set*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The *V* stands for *variety* (a specific type of algebraic set to be defined below).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Given a subset *U* of **A***n*, can one recover the set of polynomials which generate it?
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] If *U* is *any* subset of **A***n*, define *I*(*U*) to be the set of all polynomials whose vanishing set contains *U*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The *I* stands for ideal: if two polynomials *f* and *g* both vanish on *U*, then *f*+*g* vanishes on *U*, and if *h* is any polynomial, then *hf* vanishes on *U*, so *I*(*U*) is always an ideal of the polynomial ring *k*[**A***n*].
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The answer to the first question is provided by introducing the Zariski topology, a topology on **A***n* whose closed sets are the algebraic sets, and which directly reflects the algebraic structure of *k*[**A***n*].
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Then *U* = *V*(*I*(*U*)) if and only if *U* is an algebraic set or equivalently a Zariski-closed set.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The answer to the second question is given by Hilbert's Nullstellensatz.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] In one of its forms, it says that *I*(*V*(*S*)) is the radical of the ideal generated by *S*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] In more abstract language, there is a Galois connection, giving rise to two closure operators; they can be identified, and naturally play a basic role in the theory; the example is elaborated at Galois connection.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] For various reasons we may not always want to work with the entire ideal corresponding to an algebraic set *U*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Hilbert's basis theorem implies that ideals in *k*[**A***n*] are always finitely generated.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] An algebraic set is called *irreducible* if it cannot be written as the union of two smaller algebraic sets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Any algebraic set is a finite union of irreducible algebraic sets and this decomposition is unique.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Thus its elements are called the *irreducible components* of the algebraic set.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] An irreducible algebraic set is also called a *variety*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] It turns out that an algebraic set is a variety if and only if it may be defined as the vanishing set of a prime ideal of the polynomial ring.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Some authors do not make a clear distinction between algebraic sets and varieties and use *irreducible variety* to make the distinction when needed.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Just as continuous functions are the natural maps on topological spaces and smooth functions are the natural maps on differentiable manifolds, there is a natural class of functions on an algebraic set, called *regular functions* or *polynomial functions*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] A regular function on an algebraic set *V* contained in **A***n* is the restriction to *V* of a regular function on **A***n*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] For an algebraic set defined on the field of the complex numbers, the regular functions are smooth and even analytic.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Just as with the regular functions on affine space, the regular functions on *V* form a ring, which we denote by *k*[*V*].
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This ring is called the *coordinate ring of V*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Since regular functions on V come from regular functions on **A***n*, there is a relationship between the coordinate rings.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Specifically, if a regular function on *V* is the restriction of two functions *f* and *g* in *k*[**A***n*], then *f* − *g* is a polynomial function which is null on *V* and thus belongs to *I*(*V*).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Using regular functions from an affine variety to **A**1, we can define regular maps from one affine variety to another.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] First we will define a regular map from a variety into affine space: Let *V* be a variety contained in **A***n*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Choose *m* regular functions on *V*, and call them *f*1, . . ., *f**m*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] In other words, each *f**i* determines one coordinate of the range of *f*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] If *V*′ is a variety contained in **A***m*, we say that *f* is a *regular map* from *V* to *V*′ if the range of *f* is contained in *V*′.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The definition of the regular maps apply also to algebraic sets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The regular maps are also called *morphisms*, as they make the collection of all affine algebraic sets into a category, where the objects are the affine algebraic sets and the morphisms are the regular maps.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The affine varieties is a subcategory of the category of the algebraic sets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Given a regular map *g* from *V* to *V*′ and a regular function *f* of *k*[*V*′], then *f* ∘ *g* ∈ *k*[*V*].
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Conversely, every ring homomorphism from *k*[*V*′] to *k*[*V*] defines a regular map from *V* to *V*′.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This defines an equivalence of categories between the category of algebraic sets and the opposite category of the finitely generated reduced *k*-algebras.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This equivalence is one of the starting points of scheme theory.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] In contrast to the preceding sections, this section concerns only varieties and not algebraic sets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] On the other hand, the definitions extend naturally to projective varieties (next section), as an affine variety and its projective completion have the same field of functions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] If *V* is an affine variety, its coordinate ring is an integral domain and has thus a field of fractions which is denoted *k*(*V*) and called the *field of the rational functions* on *V* or, shortly, the *function field* of *V*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Its elements are the restrictions to *V* of the rational functions over the affine space containing *V*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The domain of a rational function *f* is not *V* but the complement of the sub-variety (a hypersurface) where the denominator of *f* vanishes.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] As with regular maps, one may define a *rational map* from a variety *V* to a variety *V*'.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] As with the regular maps, the rational maps from *V* to *V*' may be identified to the field homomorphisms from *k*(*V*') to *k*(*V*).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Two affine varieties are *birationally equivalent* if there are two rational functions between them which are inverse one to the other in the regions where both are defined.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Equivalently, they are birationally equivalent if their function fields are isomorphic.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] An affine variety is a *rational variety* if it is birationally equivalent to an affine space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This means that the variety admits a *rational parameterization*, that is a parametrization with rational functions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] which may also be viewed as a rational map from the line to the circle.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The problem of resolution of singularities is to know if every algebraic variety is birationally equivalent to a variety whose projective completion is non-singular (see also smooth completion).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] It was solved in the affirmative in characteristic 0 by Heisuke Hironaka in 1964 and is yet unsolved in finite characteristic.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Whereas the complex numbers are obtained by adding the number *i*, a root of the polynomial *x*2 + 1, projective space is obtained by adding in appropriate points "at infinity", points where parallel lines may meet.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] To see how this might come about, consider the variety *V*(*y* − *x*2).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] As *x* goes to positive infinity, the slope of the line from the origin to the point (*x*, *x*2) also goes to positive infinity.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] As *x* goes to negative infinity, the slope of the same line goes to negative infinity.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Compare this to the variety *V*(*y* − *x*3).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] As *x* goes to positive infinity, the slope of the line from the origin to the point (*x*, *x*3) goes to positive infinity just as before.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] But unlike before, as *x* goes to negative infinity, the slope of the same line goes to positive infinity as well; the exact opposite of the parabola.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] So the behaviour "at infinity" of *V*(*y* − *x*3) is different from the behaviour "at infinity" of *V*(*y* − *x*2).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Also, both curves are rational, as they are parameterized by *x*, and the Riemann-Roch theorem implies that the cubic curve must have a singularity, which must be at infinity, as all its points in the affine space are regular.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Thus many of the properties of algebraic varieties, including birational equivalence and all the topological properties, depend on the behavior "at infinity" and so it is natural to study the varieties in projective space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Furthermore, the introduction of projective techniques made many theorems in algebraic geometry simpler and sharper: For example, Bézout's theorem on the number of intersection points between two varieties can be stated in its sharpest form only in projective space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] For these reasons, projective space plays a fundamental role in algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Nowadays, the *projective space* **P***n* of dimension *n* is usually defined as the set of the lines passing through a point, considered as the origin, in the affine space of dimension *n* + 1, or equivalently to the set of the vector lines in a vector space of dimension *n* + 1.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] When a coordinate system has been chosen in the space of dimension *n* + 1, all the points of a line have the same set of coordinates, up to the multiplication by an element of *k*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This defines the homogeneous coordinates of a point of **P***n* as a sequence of *n* + 1 elements of the base field *k*, defined up to the multiplication by a nonzero element of *k* (the same for the whole sequence).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] A polynomial in *n* + 1 variables vanishes at all points of a line passing through the origin if and only if it is homogeneous.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] In this case, one says that the polynomial *vanishes* at the corresponding point of **P***n*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This allows us to define a *projective algebraic set* in **P***n* as the set *V*(*f*1, ..., *f**k*), where a finite set of homogeneous polynomials {*f*1, ..., *f**k*} vanishes.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Like for affine algebraic sets, there is a bijection between the projective algebraic sets and the reduced homogeneous ideals which define them.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The *projective varieties* are the projective algebraic sets whose defining ideal is prime.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Every projective algebraic set may be uniquely decomposed into a finite union of projective varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The only regular functions which may be defined properly on a projective variety are the constant functions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Thus this notion is not used in projective situations.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] On the other hand, the *field of the rational functions* or *function field* is a useful notion, which, similarly to the affine case, is defined as the set of the quotients of two homogeneous elements of the same degree in the homogeneous coordinate ring.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Real algebraic geometry is the study of real algebraic varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The fact that the field of the real numbers is an ordered field cannot be ignored in such a study.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] For example, the curve of equation $x^{2}+y^{2}-a=0$ is a circle if $a>0$ , but has no real points if $a<0$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Real algebraic geometry also investigates, more broadly, *semi-algebraic sets*, which are the solutions of systems of polynomial inequalities.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] For example, neither branch of the hyperbola of equation $xy-1=0$ is a real algebraic variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] However, the branch in the first quadrant is a semi-algebraic set defined by $xy-1=0$ and $x>0$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] One open problem in real algebraic geometry is the following part of Hilbert's sixteenth problem: Decide which respective positions are possible for the ovals of a non-singular plane curve of degree 8.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] One may date the origin of computational algebraic geometry to meeting EUROSAM'79 (International Symposium on Symbolic and Algebraic Manipulation) held at Marseille, France, in June 1979.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Since then, most results in this area are related to one or several of these items either by using or improving one of these algorithms, or by finding algorithms whose complexity is singly exponential in the number of the variables.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] A body of mathematical theory complementary to symbolic methods called numerical algebraic geometry has been developed over the last several decades.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The main computational method is homotopy continuation.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This supports, for example, a model of floating-point computation for solving problems of algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] A Gröbner basis is a system of generators of a polynomial ideal whose computation allows the deduction of many properties of the affine algebraic variety defined by the ideal.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Gröbner basis computations do not allow one to compute directly the primary decomposition of *I* nor the prime ideals defining the irreducible components of *V*, but most algorithms for this involve Gröbner basis computation.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The algorithms which are not based on Gröbner bases use regular chains but may need Gröbner bases in some exceptional situations.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Gröbner bases are deemed to be difficult to compute.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] In fact they may contain, in the worst case, polynomials whose degree is doubly exponential in the number of variables and a number of polynomials which is also doubly exponential.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] However, this is only a worst-case complexity, and the complexity bound of Lazard's algorithm of 1979 may frequently apply.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Faugère F5 algorithm realizes this complexity, as it may be viewed as an improvement of Lazard's 1979 algorithm.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] It follows that the best implementations allow one to compute almost routinely with algebraic sets of degree more than 100.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This means that, presently, the difficulty of computing a Gröbner basis is strongly related to the intrinsic difficulty of the problem.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] CAD is an algorithm which was introduced in 1973 by G.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Collins to implement with an acceptable complexity the Tarski–Seidenberg theorem on quantifier elimination over the real numbers.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This theorem concerns the formulas of the first-order logic whose atomic formulas are polynomial equalities or inequalities between polynomials with real coefficients.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] These formulas are thus the formulas which may be constructed from the atomic formulas by the logical operators *and* (∧), *or* (∨), *not* (¬), *for all* (∀), and *there exists* (∃).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Tarski's theorem asserts that, from such a formula, one may compute an equivalent formula without quantifiers (∀, ∃).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The complexity of CAD is doubly exponential in the number of variables.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This means that CAD allows one, in theory, to solve every problem of real algebraic geometry which may be expressed by such a formula—this is almost every problem concerning explicitly given varieties and semi-algebraic sets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] While Gröbner basis computation has doubly exponential complexity only in rare cases, CAD has almost always this high complexity.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This implies that, unless most polynomials appearing in the input are linear, it may not solve problems with more than four variables.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Since 1973, most of the research on this subject is devoted either to improving CAD or finding alternative algorithms in special cases of general interest.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] As an example of the state of art, there are efficient algorithms to find at least one point in every connected component of a semi-algebraic set, and thus to test whether a semi-algebraic set is empty.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] On the other hand, CAD is yet, in practice, the best algorithm to count the number of connected components.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The basic general algorithms of computational geometry have a doubly exponential worst-case complexity.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] More precisely, if *d* is the maximal degree of the input polynomials and *n* the number of variables, then their complexity is at most *d*2*cn* for some constant *c*, and, for some inputs, the complexity is at least *d*2*c′n* for another constant *c*′.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] During the last 20 years of the 20th century, various algorithms were introduced to solve specific subproblems with a better complexity.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Most of these algorithms have a complexity $d^{O(n^{2})}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The main algorithms of real algebraic geometry which solve a problem solved by CAD are related to the topology of semi-algebraic sets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] One may cite *counting the number of connected components*, *testing whether two points are in the same components*, and *computing a Whitney stratification of a real algebraic set*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] They have a complexity of $d^{O(n^{2})}$ , but the constant involved by *O* notation is so high that using them to solve any nontrivial problem effectively solved by CAD, is impossible even if one could use all the existing computing power in the world.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Therefore, these algorithms have never been implemented and it is an active research area to search for algorithms with have together a good asymptotic complexity and a good practical efficiency.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The modern approaches to algebraic geometry redefine and effectively extend the range of basic objects in various levels of generality to schemes, formal schemes, ind-schemes, algebraic spaces, algebraic stacks, and so on.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Most remarkably, in the early 1960s, algebraic varieties were subsumed into Alexander Grothendieck's concept of a scheme.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The gluing is along the Zariski topology; one can glue within the category of locally ringed spaces, but also, using the Yoneda embedding, within the more abstract category of presheaves of sets over the category of affine schemes.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The Zariski topology in the set-theoretic sense is then replaced by a Grothendieck topology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Sheaves can be furthermore generalized to stacks in the sense of Grothendieck, usually with some additional representability conditions leading to Artin stacks and, even finer, Deligne–Mumford stacks, both often called algebraic stacks.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Sometimes, other algebraic sites replace the category of affine schemes.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] For example, Nikolai Durov has introduced commutative algebraic monads as a generalization of local objects in a generalized algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Versions of a tropical geometry, of an absolute geometry over a field of one element, and an algebraic analogue of Arakelov's geometry were realized in this setup.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Another formal generalization is possible to universal algebraic geometry in which every variety of algebras has its own algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The term *variety of algebras* should not be confused with *algebraic variety*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The language of schemes, stacks, and generalizations has proved to be a valuable way of dealing with geometric concepts and become cornerstones of modern algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Algebraic stacks can be further generalized, and for many practical questions like deformation theory and intersection theory, this is often the most natural approach.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] One can also replace presheaves of sets with presheaves of simplicial sets (or of infinity groupoids).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Another (noncommutative) version of derived algebraic geometry, using A-infinity categories, has been developed from the early 1990s by Maxim Kontsevich and followers.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Some of the roots of algebraic geometry date back to the work of the Hellenistic Greeks from the 5th century BC.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The Delian problem, for instance, was to construct a length *x* so that the cube of side *x* contained the same volume as the rectangular box *a*2*b* for given sides *a* and *b*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] 350 BC) considered the problem geometrically by intersecting the pair of plane conics *ay* = *x*2 and *xy* = *ab*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] In the 3rd century BC, Archimedes and Apollonius systematically studied additional problems on conic sections using coordinates.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Apollonius in the Conics further developed a method that is so similar to analytic geometry that his work is sometimes thought to have anticipated the work of Descartes by some 1800 years.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] He further developed relations between the abscissas and the corresponding coordinates using geometric methods like using parabolas and curves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Medieval mathematicians, including Omar Khayyam, Leonardo of Pisa, Gersonides and Nicole Oresme in the Medieval Period, solved certain cubic and quadratic equations by purely algebraic means and then interpreted the results geometrically.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The Persian mathematician Omar Khayyám (born 1048 AD) believed that there was a relationship between arithmetic, algebra, and geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This was criticized by Jeffrey Oaks, who claims that the study of curves by means of equations originated with Descartes in the seventeenth century.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Such techniques of applying geometrical constructions to algebraic problems were also adopted by a number of Renaissance mathematicians such as Gerolamo Cardano and Niccolò Fontana "Tartaglia" on their studies of the cubic equation.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The geometrical approach to construction problems, rather than the algebraic one, was favored by most 16th- and 17th-century mathematicians, notably Blaise Pascal who argued against the use of algebraic and analytical methods in geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The French mathematicians Franciscus Vieta and later René Descartes and Pierre de Fermat revolutionized the conventional way of thinking about construction problems through the introduction of coordinate geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] They were interested primarily in the properties of *algebraic curves*, such as those defined by Diophantine equations (in the case of Fermat), and the algebraic reformulation of the classical Greek works on conics and cubics (in the case of Descartes).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] During the same period, Blaise Pascal and Gérard Desargues approached geometry from a different perspective, developing the synthetic notions of projective geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Pascal and Desargues also studied curves, but from the purely geometrical point of view: the analog of the Greek *ruler-and-compass construction*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Ultimately, the analytic geometry of Descartes and Fermat won out, for it supplied the 18th-century mathematicians with concrete quantitative tools needed to study physical problems using the new calculus of Newton and Leibniz.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] However, by the end of the 18th century, most of the algebraic character of coordinate geometry was subsumed by the *calculus of infinitesimals* of Lagrange and Euler.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] It took the simultaneous 19th-century developments of non-Euclidean geometry and Abelian integrals in order to bring the old algebraic ideas back into the geometrical fold.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The first of these new developments was seized up by Edmond Laguerre and Arthur Cayley, who attempted to ascertain the generalized metric properties of projective space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Cayley introduced the idea of *homogeneous polynomial forms*, and more specifically quadratic forms, on projective space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Subsequently, Felix Klein studied projective geometry (along with other types of geometry) from the viewpoint that the geometry on a space is encoded in a certain class of transformations on the space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] By the end of the 19th century, projective geometers were studying more general kinds of transformations on figures in projective space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Rather than the projective linear transformations which were normally regarded as giving the fundamental Kleinian geometry on projective space, they concerned themselves also with the higher-degree birational transformations.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] This weaker notion of congruence would later lead members of the 20th century Italian school of algebraic geometry to classify algebraic surfaces up to birational isomorphism.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The second early-19th-century development, that of Abelian integrals, would lead Bernhard Riemann to the development of Riemann surfaces.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] In the same period began the algebraization of the algebraic geometry through commutative algebra.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The prominent results in this direction are Hilbert's basis theorem and Hilbert's Nullstellensatz, which are the basis of the connection between algebraic geometry and commutative algebra, and Macaulay's multivariate resultant, which is the basis of elimination theory.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Probably because of the size of the computation which is implied by multivariate resultants, elimination theory was forgotten during the middle of the 20th century until it was renewed by singularity theory and computational algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] L. van der Waerden, Oscar Zariski, and André Weil developed a foundation for algebraic geometry based on contemporary commutative algebra, including valuation theory and the theory of ideals.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] One of the goals was to give a rigorous framework for proving the results of the Italian school of algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] In particular, this school used systematically the notion of generic point without any precise definition, which was first given by these authors during the 1930s.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] In the 1950s and 1960s, Jean-Pierre Serre and Alexander Grothendieck recast the foundations making use of sheaf theory.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Later, from about 1960, and largely led by Grothendieck, the idea of schemes was worked out, in conjunction with a very refined apparatus of homological techniques.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] After a decade of rapid development the field stabilized in the 1970s, and new applications were made, both to number theory and to more classical geometric questions on algebraic varieties, singularities, moduli, and formal moduli.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] An important class of varieties, not easily understood directly from their defining equations, are the abelian varieties, which are the projective varieties whose points form an abelian group.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The prototypical examples are the elliptic curves, which have a rich theory.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] They were instrumental in the proof of Fermat's Last Theorem and are also used in elliptic-curve cryptography.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] In parallel with the abstract trend of the algebraic geometry, which is concerned with general statements about varieties, methods for effective computation with concretely-given varieties have also been developed, which lead to the new area of computational algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] One of the founding methods of this area is the theory of Gröbner bases, introduced by Bruno Buchberger in 1965.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Another founding method, more specially devoted to real algebraic geometry, is the cylindrical algebraic decomposition, introduced by George E.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] An **analytic variety** over the field of real or complex numbers is defined locally as the set of common solutions of several equations involving analytic functions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] It is analogous to the concept of algebraic variety in that it carries a structure sheaf of analytic functions instead of regular functions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Any complex manifold is a complex analytic variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Since analytic varieties may have singular points, not all complex analytic varieties are manifolds.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Over a non-archimedean field analytic geometry is studied via rigid analytic spaces.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Modern analytic geometry over the field of complex numbers is closely related to complex algebraic geometry, as has been shown by Jean-Pierre Serre in his paper *GAGA*, the name of which is French for *Algebraic geometry and analytic geometry*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] The GAGA results over the field of complex numbers may be extended to rigid analytic spaces over non-archimedean fields.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] Algebraic geometry now finds applications in statistics, control theory, robotics, error-correcting codes, phylogenetics and geometric modelling.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-geometry] There are also connections to string theory, game theory, graph matchings, solitons and integer programming.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Conventions regarding the definition of an algebraic variety differ slightly.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] For example, some definitions require an algebraic variety to be irreducible, which means that it is not the union of two smaller sets that are closed in the Zariski topology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Under this definition, non-irreducible algebraic varieties are called **algebraic sets**.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Other conventions do not require irreducibility.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The fundamental theorem of algebra establishes a link between algebra and geometry by showing that a monic polynomial (an algebraic object) in one variable with complex number coefficients is determined by the set of its roots (a geometric object) in the complex plane.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Generalizing this result, Hilbert's Nullstellensatz provides a fundamental correspondence between ideals of polynomial rings and algebraic sets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Using the *Nullstellensatz* and related results, mathematicians have established a strong correspondence between questions on algebraic sets and questions of ring theory.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] This correspondence is a defining feature of algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Many algebraic varieties are differentiable manifolds, but an algebraic variety may have singular points while a differentiable manifold cannot.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Algebraic varieties can be characterized by their dimension.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Algebraic varieties of dimension one are called *algebraic curves* and algebraic varieties of dimension two are called *algebraic surfaces*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] In the context of modern scheme theory, an algebraic variety over a field is an integral (irreducible and reduced) scheme over that field whose structure morphism is separated and of finite type.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] An *affine variety* over an algebraically closed field is conceptually the easiest type of variety to define, which will be done in this section.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Next, one can define projective and quasi-projective varieties in a similar way.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The most general definition of a variety is obtained by patching together smaller quasi-projective varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] It is not obvious that one can construct genuinely new examples of varieties in this way, but Nagata gave an example of such a new variety in the 1950s.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] For an algebraically closed field K and a natural number n, let **A***n* be an affine *n*-space over *K*, identified to *K**n* through the choice of an affine coordinate system.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The polynomials *f* in the ring *K*[*x*1, ..., *xn*] can be viewed as *K*-valued functions on **A***n* by evaluating *f* at the points in **A***n*, i.e. by choosing values in *K* for each *xi*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] A subset *V* of **A***n* is called an **affine algebraic set** if *V* = *Z*(*S*) for some *S*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] A nonempty affine algebraic set *V* is called **irreducible** if it cannot be written as the union of two proper algebraic subsets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] An irreducible affine algebraic set is also called an **affine variety**.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Affine varieties can be given a natural topology by declaring the closed sets to be precisely the affine algebraic sets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] This topology is called the Zariski topology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] For any affine algebraic set *V*, the **coordinate ring** or **structure ring** of *V* is the quotient of the polynomial ring by this ideal.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Let k be an algebraically closed field and let **P***n* be the projective *n*-space over k.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Let *f* in *k*[*x*0, ..., *xn*] be a homogeneous polynomial of degree *d*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] It is not well-defined to evaluate *f* on points in **P***n* in homogeneous coordinates.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] A subset *V* of **P***n* is called a **projective algebraic set** if *V* = *Z*(*S*) for some *S*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] An irreducible projective algebraic set is called a **projective variety**.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Projective varieties are also equipped with the Zariski topology by declaring all algebraic sets to be closed.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Given a subset *V* of **P***n*, let *I*(*V*) be the ideal generated by all homogeneous polynomials vanishing on *V*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] For any projective algebraic set *V*, the **coordinate ring** of *V* is the quotient of the polynomial ring by this ideal.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] A **quasi-projective variety** is a Zariski open subset of a projective variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Notice that every affine variety is quasi-projective using *x*0 = 0 chart.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Notice also that the complement of an algebraic set in an affine variety is a quasi-projective variety; in the context of affine varieties, such a quasi-projective variety is usually not called a variety but a constructible set.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] In classical algebraic geometry, all varieties were by definition quasi-projective varieties, meaning that they were open subvarieties of closed subvarieties of a projective space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] So classically the definition of an algebraic variety required an embedding into projective space, and this embedding was used to define the topology on the variety and the regular functions on the variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The disadvantage of such a definition is that not all varieties come with natural embeddings into projective space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] For example, under this definition, the product **P**1 × **P**1 is not a variety until it is embedded into a larger projective space; this is usually done by the Segre embedding.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Furthermore, any variety that admits one embedding into projective space admits many others, for example by composing the embedding with the Veronese embedding; thus many notions that should be intrinsic, such as that of a regular function, are not obviously so.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The earliest successful attempt to define an algebraic variety abstractly, without an embedding, was made by André Weil in his *Foundations of Algebraic Geometry,* using valuations.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Claude Chevalley made a definition of a scheme, which served a similar purpose, but was more general.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] However, Alexander Grothendieck's definition of a scheme is more general still and has received the most widespread acceptance.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Classical algebraic varieties are the quasiprojective integral separated finite type schemes over an algebraically closed field.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] One of the earliest examples of a non-quasiprojective algebraic variety were given by Nagata.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Nagata's example was not complete (the analog of compactness), but soon afterwards he found an algebraic surface that was complete and non-projective.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Since then other examples have been found: for example, it is straightforward to construct toric varieties that are not quasi-projective but complete.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] A **subvariety** is a subset of a variety that is itself a variety (with respect to the topological structure induced by the ambient variety).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] For example, every open subset of a variety is a variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Hilbert's Nullstellensatz says that closed subvarieties of an affine or projective variety are in one-to-one correspondence with the prime ideals or non-irrelevant homogeneous prime ideals of the coordinate ring of the variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Let *k* = **C**, and **A**2 be the two-dimensional affine space over **C**.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Polynomials in the ring **C**[*x*, *y*] can be viewed as complex valued functions on **A**2 by evaluating at the points in **A**2.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The zero-locus of *f*(*x*, *y*) is the set of points in **A**2 on which this function vanishes: it is the set of all pairs of complex numbers (*x*, *y*) such that *y* = 1 − *x*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] This is called a line in the affine plane.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Thus the subset *V* = *Z*(*f*) of **A**2 is an algebraic set.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] It is irreducible, as it cannot be written as the union of two proper algebraic subsets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The zero-locus of *g*(*x*, *y*) is the set of points in **A**2 on which this function vanishes, that is the set of points (*x*, *y*) such that *x*2 + *y*2 = 1.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] As *g*(*x*, *y*) is an absolutely irreducible polynomial, this is an algebraic variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The set of its real points (that is the points for which *x* and *y* are real numbers), is known as the unit circle; this name is also often given to the whole variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The following example is neither a hypersurface, nor a linear space, nor a single point.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Let **A**3 be the three-dimensional affine space over **C**.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The set of points (*x*, *x*2, *x*3) for *x* in **C** is an algebraic variety, and more precisely an algebraic curve that is not contained in any plane.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] It is the twisted cubic shown in the above figure.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The irreducibility of this algebraic set needs a proof.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] One approach in this case is to check that the projection (*x*, *y*, *z*) ↦ (*x*, *y*) is injective on the set of the solutions and that its image is an irreducible plane curve.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The set of *n*-by-*n* matrices over the base field *k* can be identified with the affine *n*2-space **A***n*2 with coordinates *x**ij* such that *x**ij*(*A*) is the (*i*, *j*)th entry of the matrix *A*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The determinant det is then a polynomial in *x**ij* and thus defines the hypersurface *H* = *V*(det) in **A***n*2.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The complement of *H* is then an open subset of **A***n*2 that consists of all the invertible *n*-by-*n* matrices, the general linear group GL*n*(*k*).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] It is an affine variety, since, in general, the complement of a hypersurface in an affine variety is affine.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Explicitly, consider **A***n*2 × **A**1, where the affine line is given coordinate *t*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] i.e., the set of matrices *A* such that *t* det(*A*) = 1 has a solution.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The multiplicative group *k*× of the base field *k* is the same as GL1(*k*) and thus is an affine variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] A finite product of it (*k*×)*r* is an algebraic torus, which is again an affine variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] A general linear group is an example of a linear algebraic group, an affine variety that has a structure of a group in such a way the group operations are morphism of varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Let *A* be a not-necessarily-commutative algebra over a field *k*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] For example, if *A* is the universal enveloping algebra of a finite-dimensional Lie algebra ${\mathfrak {g}}$ , then gr *A* is a polynomial ring (the PBW theorem); more precisely, the coordinate ring of the dual vector space ${\mathfrak {g}}^{*}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] If gr *M* is finitely generated as a gr *A*-algebra, then the support of gr *M* in *X*; i.e., the locus where gr *M* does not vanish is called the characteristic variety of *M*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The notion plays an important role in the theory of *D*-modules.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] A projective variety is a closed subvariety of a projective space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] That is, it is the zero locus of a set of homogeneous polynomials that generate a prime ideal.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] A plane projective curve is the zero locus of an irreducible homogeneous polynomial in three indeterminates.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The projective line **P**1 is an example of a projective curve; it can be viewed as the curve in the projective plane **P**2 = {[*x*, *y*, *z*]} defined by *x* = 0.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] in the 2-dimensional affine space (over a field of characteristic not two).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] which defines a curve in **P**2 called an elliptic curve.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The curve has genus one (genus formula); in particular, it is not isomorphic to the projective line **P**1, which has genus zero.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Using genus to distinguish curves is very basic: in fact, the genus is the first invariant one uses to classify curves (see also the construction of moduli of algebraic curves).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Let *V* be a finite-dimensional vector space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The Grassmannian variety *Gn*(*V*) is the set of all *n*-dimensional subspaces of *V*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] where *bi* are any set of linearly independent vectors in *V*, $\wedge ^{n}V$ is the *n*th exterior power of *V*, and the bracket [*w*] means the line spanned by the nonzero vector *w*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The Grassmannian variety comes with a natural vector bundle (or locally free sheaf in other terminology) called the tautological bundle, which is important in the study of characteristic classes such as Chern classes.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Let *C* be a smooth complete curve and Pic(*C*) the Picard group of it; i.e., the group of isomorphism classes of line bundles on *C*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Since *C* is smooth, Pic(*C*) can be identified as the divisor class group of *C* and thus there is the degree homomorphism deg : Pic(*C*) → **Z**.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The Jacobian variety Jac(*C*) of *C* is the kernel of this degree map; i.e., the group of the divisor classes on *C* of degree zero.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] A Jacobian variety is an example of an abelian variety, a complete variety with a compatible abelian group structure on it (the name "abelian" is however not because it is an abelian group).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] An abelian variety turns out to be projective (in short, algebraic theta functions give an embedding into a projective space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] See equations defining abelian varieties); thus, Jac(*C*) is a projective variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The tangent space to Jac(*C*) at the identity element is naturally isomorphic to $\operatorname {H} ^{1}(C,{\mathcal {O}}_{C});$ hence, the dimension of Jac(*C*) is the genus of *C*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] where *C**n* is the product of *n* copies of *C*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] For *g* = 1 (i.e., *C* is an elliptic curve), the above morphism for *n* = 1 turns out to be an isomorphism; in particular, an elliptic curve is an abelian variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Given an integer *g* ≥ 0, the set of isomorphism classes of smooth complete curves of genus *g* is called the moduli of curves of genus g and is denoted as ${\mathfrak {M}}_{g}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] There are few ways to show this moduli has a structure of a possibly reducible algebraic variety; for example, one way is to use geometric invariant theory which ensures a set of isomorphism classes has a (reducible) quasi-projective variety structure.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Moduli such as the moduli of curves of fixed genus is typically not a projective variety; roughly the reason is that a degeneration (limit) of a smooth curve tends to be non-smooth or reducible.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] This leads to the notion of a stable curve of genus *g* ≥ 2, a not-necessarily-smooth complete curve with no terribly bad singularities and not-so-large automorphism group.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The moduli of stable curves ${\overline {\mathfrak {M}}}_{g}$ , the set of isomorphism classes of stable curves of genus *g* ≥ 2, is then a projective variety which contains ${\mathfrak {M}}_{g}$ as an open dense subset.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Since ${\overline {\mathfrak {M}}}_{g}$ is obtained by adding boundary points to ${\mathfrak {M}}_{g}$ , ${\overline {\mathfrak {M}}}_{g}$ is colloquially said to be a compactification of ${\mathfrak {M}}_{g}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Historically a paper of Mumford and Deligne introduced the notion of a stable curve to show ${\mathfrak {M}}_{g}$ is irreducible when *g* ≥ 2.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The moduli of curves exemplifies a typical situation: a moduli of nice objects tend not to be projective but only quasi-projective.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Another case is a moduli of vector bundles on a curve.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Here, there are the notions of stable and semistable vector bundles on a smooth complete curve *C*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Since a line bundle is stable, such a moduli is a generalization of the Jacobian variety of *C*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] In general, in contrast to the case of moduli of curves, a compactification of a moduli need not be unique and, in some cases, different non-equivalent compactifications are constructed using different methods and by different authors.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] An example over **C** is the problem of compactifying *D* / Γ, the quotient of a bounded symmetric domain *D* by an action of an arithmetic discrete group Γ.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The theory of toric varieties (or torus embeddings) gives a way to compactify *D* / Γ, a toroidal compactification of it.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] But there are other ways to compactify *D* / Γ; for example, there is the minimal compactification of *D* / Γ due to Baily and Borel: it is the projective variety associated to the graded ring formed by modular forms (in the Siegel case, Siegel modular forms; see also Siegel modular variety).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] An algebraic variety can be neither affine nor projective.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Here *X* is an algebraic variety since it is a product of varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] It is not affine since **P**1 is a closed subvariety of *X* (as the zero locus of *p*), but an affine variety cannot contain a projective variety of positive dimension as a closed subvariety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] It is not projective either, since there is a nonconstant regular function on *X*; namely, *p*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Another example of a non-affine non-projective variety is *X* = **A**2 − (0, 0) (cf.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Consider the affine line **A**1 over **C**.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The complement of the circle { *z* ∈ **C** : |*z*|2 = 1 } in **A**1 = **C** is not an algebraic variety (nor even an algebraic set).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Note that |z|2 − 1 is not a polynomial in *z* (although it is a polynomial in the real coordinates *x*, *y*).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] On the other hand, the complement of the origin in **A**1 = **C** is an algebraic (affine) variety, since the origin is the zero-locus of *z*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] This may be explained as follows: the affine line has dimension one and so any subvariety of it other than itself must have strictly less dimension; namely, zero.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] For similar reasons, a unitary group (over the complex numbers) is not an algebraic variety, while the special linear group SL*n*(**C**) is a closed subvariety of GL*n*(**C**), the zero-locus of det − 1.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] We say *V*1 and *V*2 are isomorphic, and write *V*1 ≅ *V*2, if there are regular maps *φ* : *V*1 → *V*2 and *ψ* : *V*2 → *V*1 such that the compositions *ψ* ∘ *φ* and *φ* ∘ *ψ* are the identity maps on *V*1 and *V*2 respectively.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The basic definitions and facts above enable one to do classical algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] To be able to do more – for example, to deal with varieties over fields that are not algebraically closed – some foundational changes are required.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] The modern notion of a variety is considerably more abstract than the one above, though equivalent in the case of varieties over algebraically closed fields.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] An *abstract algebraic variety* is a particular kind of scheme; the generalization to schemes on the geometric side enables an extension of the correspondence described above to a wider class of rings.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] A scheme is a locally ringed space such that every point has a neighbourhood that, as a locally ringed space, is isomorphic to a spectrum of a ring.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Basically, a variety over k is a scheme whose structure sheaf is a sheaf of k-algebras with the property that the rings *R* that occur above are all integral domains and are all finitely generated k-algebras, that is to say, they are quotients of polynomial algebras by prime ideals.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] It allows you to glue affine varieties (along common open sets) without worrying whether the resulting object can be put into some projective space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] This also leads to difficulties since one can introduce somewhat pathological objects, e.g. an affine line with zero doubled.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Such objects are usually not considered varieties, and are eliminated by requiring the schemes underlying a variety to be *separated*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Some modern researchers also remove the restriction on a variety having integral domain affine charts, and when speaking of a variety only require that the affine charts have trivial nilradical.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] A complete variety is a variety such that any map from an open subset of a nonsingular curve into it can be extended uniquely to the whole curve.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Every projective variety is complete, but not vice versa.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] These varieties have been called "varieties in the sense of Serre", since Serre's foundational paper FAC on sheaf cohomology was written for them.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] They remain typical objects to start studying in algebraic geometry, even if more general objects are also used in an auxiliary way.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] One way that leads to generalizations is to allow reducible algebraic sets (and fields k that aren't algebraically closed), so the rings *R* may not be integral domains.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] A more significant modification is to allow nilpotents in the sheaf of rings, that is, rings which are not **reduced**.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] This is one of several generalizations of classical algebraic geometry that are built into Grothendieck's theory of schemes.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Allowing nilpotent elements in rings is related to keeping track of "multiplicities" in algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] For example, the closed subscheme of the affine line defined by *x*2 = 0 is different from the subscheme defined by *x* = 0 (the origin).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] More generally, the fiber of a morphism of schemes *X* → *Y* at a point of *Y* may be non-reduced, even if *X* and *Y* are reduced.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Geometrically, this says that fibers of good mappings may have nontrivial "infinitesimal" structure.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] There are further generalizations called algebraic spaces and stacks.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] An algebraic manifold is an algebraic variety that is also an *m*-dimensional manifold, and hence every sufficiently small local patch is isomorphic to *km*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Equivalently, the variety is smooth (free from singular points).
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] When k is the real numbers, **R**, algebraic manifolds are called Nash manifolds.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Algebraic manifolds can be defined as the zero set of a finite collection of analytic algebraic functions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/algebraic-variety] Projective algebraic manifolds are an equivalent definition for projective varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] In algebraic geometry, **divisors** are a generalization of codimension-1 subvarieties of algebraic varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Two different generalizations are in common use, Cartier divisors and Weil divisors (named for Pierre Cartier and André Weil by David Mumford).
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Both are derived from the notion of divisibility in the integers and algebraic number fields.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Globally, every codimension-1 subvariety of a projective space is defined by the vanishing of one homogeneous polynomial; by contrast, a codimension-*r* subvariety need not be definable by only *r* equations when *r* is greater than 1.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] (That is, not every subvariety of projective space is a complete intersection.) Locally, every codimension-1 subvariety of a smooth variety can be defined by one equation in a neighborhood of each point.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Again, the analogous statement fails for higher-codimension subvarieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] As a result of this property, much of algebraic geometry studies an arbitrary variety by analysing its codimension-1 subvarieties and the corresponding line bundles.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] On singular varieties, this property can also fail, and so one has to distinguish between codimension-1 subvarieties and varieties which can locally be defined by one equation.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The former are Weil divisors while the latter are Cartier divisors.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Topologically, Weil divisors correspond to homology cycles, while Cartier divisors correspond to cohomology classes defined by line bundles.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] On a smooth variety (or more generally a regular scheme), a result analogous to Poincaré duality says that Weil and Cartier divisors are the same.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The name "divisor" goes back to the work of Dedekind and Weber, who showed the relevance of Dedekind domains to the study of algebraic curves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The group of divisors on a curve (the free abelian group generated by all divisors) is closely related to the group of fractional ideals for a Dedekind domain.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] An algebraic cycle is a higher codimension generalization of a divisor; by definition, a Weil divisor is a cycle of codimension 1.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] A Riemann surface is a 1-dimensional complex manifold, and so its codimension-1 submanifolds have dimension 0.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The group of divisors on a compact Riemann surface *X* is the free abelian group on the points of *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Equivalently, a divisor on a compact Riemann surface *X* is a finite linear combination of points of *X* with integer coefficients.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The **degree** of a divisor on *X* is the sum of its coefficients.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] For any nonzero meromorphic function *f* on *X*, one can define the order of vanishing of *f* at a point *p* in *X*, ord*p*(*f*).
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] It is an integer, negative if *f* has a pole at *p*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Divisors of the form (*f*) are also called **principal divisors**.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Since (*fg*) = (*f*) + (*g*), the set of principal divisors is a subgroup of the group of divisors.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Two divisors that differ by a principal divisor are called **linearly equivalent**.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] On a compact Riemann surface, the degree of a principal divisor is zero; that is, the number of zeros of a meromorphic function is equal to the number of poles, counted with multiplicity.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] As a result, the degree is well-defined on linear equivalence classes of divisors.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Given a divisor *D* on a compact Riemann surface *X*, it is important to study the complex vector space of meromorphic functions on *X* with poles at most given by *D*, called *H*0(*X*, *O*(*D*)) or the **space of sections of the line bundle** associated to *D*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The degree of *D* says a lot about the dimension of this vector space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] For example, if *D* has negative degree, then this vector space is zero (because a meromorphic function cannot have more zeros than poles).
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] If *D* has positive degree, then the dimension of *H*0(*X*, *O*(*mD*)) grows linearly in *m* for *m* sufficiently large.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The Riemann–Roch theorem is a more precise statement along these lines.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] On the other hand, the precise dimension of *H*0(*X*, *O*(*D*)) for divisors *D* of low degree is subtle, and not completely determined by the degree of *D*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The distinctive features of a compact Riemann surface are reflected in these dimensions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] One key divisor on a compact Riemann surface is the canonical divisor.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] To define it, one first defines the divisor of a nonzero meromorphic 1-form along the lines above.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Since the space of meromorphic 1-forms is a 1-dimensional vector space over the field of meromorphic functions, any two nonzero meromorphic 1-forms yield linearly equivalent divisors.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Any divisor in this linear equivalence class is called the **canonical divisor** of *X*, *K**X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The genus *g* of *X* can be read from the canonical divisor: namely, *K**X* has degree 2*g* − 2.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The key trichotomy among compact Riemann surfaces *X* is whether the canonical divisor has negative degree (so *X* has genus zero), zero degree (genus one), or positive degree (genus at least 2).
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] For example, this determines whether *X* has a Kähler metric with positive curvature, zero curvature, or negative curvature.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The canonical divisor has negative degree if and only if *X* is isomorphic to the Riemann sphere **CP**1.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Let *X* be an integral locally Noetherian scheme.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] A **prime divisor** or **irreducible divisor** on *X* is an integral closed subscheme *Z* of codimension 1 in *X*.
