[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The **Weil divisor class group** Cl(*X*) is the quotient of Div(*X*) by the subgroup of all principal Weil divisors.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Two divisors are said to be **linearly equivalent** if their difference is principal, so the divisor class group is the group of divisors modulo linear equivalence.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] For a variety *X* of dimension *n* over a field, the divisor class group is a Chow group; namely, Cl(*X*) is the Chow group CH*n*−1(*X*) of (*n*−1)-dimensional cycles.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] If *Z* is irreducible of codimension one, then Cl(*X* − *Z*) is isomorphic to the quotient group of Cl(*X*) by the class of *Z*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] If *Z* has codimension at least 2 in *X*, then the restriction Cl(*X*) → Cl(*X* − *Z*) is an isomorphism.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] On a normal integral Noetherian scheme *X*, two Weil divisors *D*, *E* are linearly equivalent if and only if ${\mathcal {O}}(D)$ and ${\mathcal {O}}(E)$ are isomorphic as ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ -modules.
