[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Cartier divisors also have a sheaf-theoretic description.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] If the Cartier divisor is denoted *D*, then the corresponding fractional ideal sheaf is denoted ${\mathcal {O}}(D)$ or *L*(*D*).
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] A Cartier divisor is said to be **principal** if it is in the image of the homomorphism $H^{0}(X,{\mathcal {M}}_{X}^{\times })\to H^{0}(X,{\mathcal {M}}_{X}^{\times }/{\mathcal {O}}_{X}^{\times }),$ that is, if it is the divisor of a rational function on *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Two Cartier divisors are **linearly equivalent** if their difference is principal.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Every line bundle *L* on an integral Noetherian scheme *X* is the class of some Cartier divisor.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] As a result, the exact sequence above identifies the Picard group of line bundles on an integral Noetherian scheme *X* with the group of Cartier divisors modulo linear equivalence.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] This holds more generally for reduced Noetherian schemes, or for quasi-projective schemes over a Noetherian ring, but it can fail in general (even for proper schemes over **C**), which lessens the interest of Cartier divisors in full generality.
