[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Because *D* is a Cartier divisor, ${\mathcal {O}}(D)$ is locally free, and hence tensoring that sequence by ${\mathcal {O}}(D)$ yields another short exact sequence, the one above.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] When *D* is smooth, ${\mathcal {O}}_{D}(D)$ is the normal bundle of *D* in *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] A Weil divisor *D* is said to be **Cartier** if and only if the sheaf ${\mathcal {O}}(D)$ is invertible.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] When this happens, ${\mathcal {O}}(D)$ (with its embedding in *MX*) is the line bundle associated to a Cartier divisor.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] More precisely, if ${\mathcal {O}}(D)$ is invertible, then there exists an open cover {*Ui*} such that ${\mathcal {O}}(D)$ restricts to a trivial bundle on each open set.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Because ${\mathcal {O}}(D)$ is defined to be a subsheaf of the sheaf of rational functions, the image of 1 may be identified with some rational function *fi*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The collection $\{(U_{i},f_{i})\}$ is then a Cartier divisor.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] This is well-defined because the only choices involved were of the covering and of the isomorphism, neither of which change the Cartier divisor.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] This Cartier divisor may be used to produce a sheaf, which for distinction we will notate *L*(*D*).
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] There is an isomorphism of ${\mathcal {O}}(D)$ with *L*(*D*) defined by working on the open cover {*Ui*}.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] In the opposite direction, a Cartier divisor $\{(U_{i},f_{i})\}$ on an integral Noetherian scheme *X* determines a Weil divisor on *X* in a natural way, by applying $\operatorname {div}$ to the functions *fi* on the open sets *Ui*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] If *X* is normal, a Cartier divisor is determined by the associated Weil divisor, and a Weil divisor is Cartier if and only if it is locally principal.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] A Noetherian scheme *X* is called **factorial** if all local rings of *X* are unique factorization domains.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] (Some authors say "locally factorial".) In particular, every regular scheme is factorial.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] On a factorial scheme *X*, every Weil divisor *D* is locally principal, and so ${\mathcal {O}}(D)$ is always a line bundle.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] In general, however, a Weil divisor on a normal scheme need not be locally principal; see the examples of quadric cones above.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Effective Cartier divisors are those which correspond to ideal sheaves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] In fact, the theory of effective Cartier divisors can be developed without any reference to sheaves of rational functions or fractional ideal sheaves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] An **effective Cartier divisor** on *X* is an ideal sheaf *I* which is invertible and such that for every point *x* in *X*, the stalk *Ix* is principal.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] It is equivalent to require that around each *x*, there exists an open affine subset *U* = Spec *A* such that *U* ∩ *D* = Spec *A* / (*f*), where *f* is a non-zero divisor in *A*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The sum of two effective Cartier divisors corresponds to multiplication of ideal sheaves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] There is a good theory of families of effective Cartier divisors.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] A **relative effective Cartier divisor** for *X* over *S* is an effective Cartier divisor *D* on *X* which is flat over *S*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Because of the flatness assumption, for every $S'\to S,$ there is a pullback of *D* to $X\times _{S}S',$ and this pullback is an effective Cartier divisor.
