[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Let φ : *X* → *Y* be a morphism of integral locally Noetherian schemes.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] It is often—but not always—possible to use φ to transfer a divisor *D* from one scheme to the other.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Whether this is possible depends on whether the divisor is a Weil or Cartier divisor, whether the divisor is to be moved from *X* to *Y* or vice versa, and what additional properties φ might have.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] If *Z* is a prime Weil divisor on *X*, then ${\overline {\varphi (Z)}}$ is a closed irreducible subscheme of *Y*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Depending on φ, it may or may not be a prime Weil divisor.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] For example, if φ is the blow up of a point in the plane and *Z* is the exceptional divisor, then its image is not a Weil divisor.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Therefore, φ**Z* is defined to be ${\overline {\varphi (Z)}}$ if that subscheme is a prime divisor and is defined to be the zero divisor otherwise.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Extending this by linearity will, assuming *X* is quasi-compact, define a homomorphism Div(*X*) → Div(*Y*) called the **pushforward**.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] (If *X* is not quasi-compact, then the pushforward may fail to be a locally finite sum.) This is a special case of the pushforward on Chow groups.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] If *Z* is a Cartier divisor, then under mild hypotheses on φ, there is a **pullback** $\varphi ^{*}Z$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Sheaf-theoretically, when there is a pullback map $\varphi ^{-1}{\mathcal {M}}_{Y}\to {\mathcal {M}}_{X}$ , then this pullback can be used to define pullback of Cartier divisors.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] Pullback is always defined if φ is dominant, but it cannot be defined in general.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] For example, if *X* = *Z* and φ is the inclusion of *Z* into *Y*, then φ**Z* is undefined because the corresponding local sections would be everywhere zero.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] If φ is flat, then pullback of Weil divisors is defined.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] In this case, the pullback of *Z* is φ**Z* = φ−1(*Z*).
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] The flatness of φ ensures that the inverse image of *Z* continues to have codimension one.
[src:algebraic-geometry/divisor-algebraic-geometry] This can fail for morphisms which are not flat, for example, for a small contraction.
