[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The other definition, which is mentioned in the previous section, is that the degree of *X* is the leading coefficient of the Hilbert polynomial of *X* times (dim *X*)!.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Geometrically, this definition means that the degree of *X* is the multiplicity of the vertex of the affine cone over *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Let $V_{1},\dots ,V_{r}\subset \mathbb {P} ^{N}$ be closed subschemes of pure dimensions that intersect properly (they are in general position).
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The intersection multiplicity *mi* can be defined as the coefficient of *Zi* in the intersection product $V_{1}\cdot \cdots \cdot V_{r}$ in the Chow ring of $\mathbb {P} ^{N}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] where *Zi* are the irreducible components of the scheme-theoretic intersection of *X* and *H* with multiplicity (length of the local ring) *mi*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] A complex projective variety can be viewed as a compact complex manifold; the degree of the variety (relative to the embedding) is then the volume of the variety as a manifold with respect to the metric inherited from the ambient complex projective space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] A complex projective variety can be characterized as a minimizer of the volume (in a sense).
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Let *X* be a projective variety and *L* a line bundle on it.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] If *L* is ample, then Proj of this ring is *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Moreover, if *X* is normal and *L* is very ample, then $R(X,L)$ is the integral closure of the homogeneous coordinate ring of *X* determined by *L*; i.e., $X\hookrightarrow \mathbb {P} ^{N}$ so that ${\mathcal {O}}_{\mathbb {P} ^{N}}(1)$ pulls-back to *L*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] For applications, it is useful to allow for divisors (or $\mathbb {Q}$ -divisors) not just line bundles; assuming *X* is normal, the resulting ring is then called a generalized ring of sections.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] If the canonical ring is finitely generated, then Proj of the ring is called the canonical model of *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The canonical ring or model can then be used to define the Kodaira dimension of *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Projective schemes of dimension one are called *projective curves*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Much of the theory of projective curves is about smooth projective curves, since the singularities of curves can be resolved by normalization, which consists in taking locally the integral closure of the ring of regular functions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Smooth projective curves are isomorphic if and only if their function fields are isomorphic.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] or equivalently smooth projective curves over $\mathbb {F} _{p}$ is an important branch in algebraic number theory.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] A smooth projective curve of genus one is called an elliptic curve.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] As a consequence of the Riemann–Roch theorem, such a curve can be embedded as a closed subvariety in $\mathbb {P} ^{2}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] In general, any (smooth) projective curve can be embedded in $\mathbb {P} ^{3}$ (for a proof, see Secant variety#Examples).
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Conversely, any smooth closed curve in $\mathbb {P} ^{2}$ of degree three has genus one by the genus formula and is thus an elliptic curve.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] A smooth complete curve of genus greater than or equal to two is called a hyperelliptic curve if there is a finite morphism $C\to \mathbb {P} ^{1}$ of degree two.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Every irreducible closed subset of $\mathbb {P} ^{n}$ of codimension one is a hypersurface; i.e., the zero set of some homogeneous irreducible polynomial.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Another important invariant of a projective variety *X* is the Picard group $\operatorname {Pic} (X)$ of *X*, the set of isomorphism classes of line bundles on *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] It is isomorphic to $H^{1}(X,{\mathcal {O}}_{X}^{*})$ and therefore an intrinsic notion (independent of embedding).
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] For example, the Picard group of $\mathbb {P} ^{n}$ is isomorphic to $\mathbb {Z}$ via the degree map.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The kernel of $\deg :\operatorname {Pic} (X)\to \mathbb {Z}$ is not only an abstract abelian group, but there is a variety called the Jacobian variety of *X*, Jac(*X*), whose points equal this group.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The Jacobian of a (smooth) curve plays an important role in the study of the curve.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] For example, the Jacobian of an elliptic curve *E* is *E* itself.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] For a curve *X* of genus *g*, Jac(*X*) has dimension *g*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Varieties, such as the Jacobian variety, which are complete and have a group structure are known as abelian varieties, in honor of Niels Abel.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] In marked contrast to affine algebraic groups such as $GL_{n}(k)$ , such groups are always commutative, whence the name.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Moreover, they admit an ample line bundle and are thus projective.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] On the other hand, an abelian scheme may not be projective.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Examples of abelian varieties are elliptic curves, Jacobian varieties and K3 surfaces.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Let $E\subset \mathbb {P} ^{n}$ be a linear subspace; i.e., $E=\{s_{0}=s_{1}=\cdots =s_{r}=0\}$ for some linearly independent linear functionals *si*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Projections can be used to cut down the dimension in which a projective variety is embedded, up to finite morphisms.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Start with some projective variety $X\subset \mathbb {P} ^{n}.$ If $n>\dim X,$ the projection from a point not on *X* gives $\phi :X\to \mathbb {P} ^{n-1}.$ Moreover, $\phi$ is a finite map to its image.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] This result is the projective analog of Noether's normalization lemma.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The same procedure can be used to show the following slightly more precise result: given a projective variety *X* over a perfect field, there is a finite birational morphism from *X* to a hypersurface *H* in $\mathbb {P} ^{d+1}.$ In particular, if *X* is normal, then it is the normalization of *H*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] While a projective *n*-space $\mathbb {P} ^{n}$ parameterizes the lines in an affine *n*-space, the dual of it parametrizes the hyperplanes on the projective space, as follows.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] For each *L*, the construction is a bijection between the set of *L*-points of ${\breve {\mathbb {P} }}_{k}^{n}$ and the set of hyperplanes on $\mathbb {P} _{L}^{n}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Because of this, the dual projective space ${\breve {\mathbb {P} }}_{k}^{n}$ is said to be the moduli space of hyperplanes on $\mathbb {P} _{k}^{n}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] A line in ${\breve {\mathbb {P} }}_{k}^{n}$ is called a pencil: it is a family of hyperplanes on $\mathbb {P} _{k}^{n}$ parametrized by $\mathbb {P} _{k}^{1}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] If *V* is a finite-dimensional vector space over *k*, then, for the same reason as above, $\mathbb {P} (V^{*})=\operatorname {Proj} (\operatorname {Sym} (V))$ is the space of hyperplanes on $\mathbb {P} (V)$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] An important case is when *V* consists of sections of a line bundle.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Namely, let *X* be an algebraic variety, *L* a line bundle on *X* and $V\subset \Gamma (X,L)$ a vector subspace of finite positive dimension.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] determined by the linear system *V*, where *B*, called the base locus, is the intersection of the divisors of zero of nonzero sections in *V* (see Linear system of divisors#A map determined by a linear system for the construction of the map).
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Let *X* be a projective scheme over a field (or, more generally over a Noetherian ring *A*).
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] where in the right-hand side ${\mathcal {F}}$ is viewed as a sheaf on the projective space by extension by zero.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The result then follows by a direct computation for ${\mathcal {F}}={\mathcal {O}}_{\mathbb {P} ^{r}}(n),$ *n* any integer, and for arbitrary ${\mathcal {F}}$ reduces to this case without much difficulty.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] As a corollary to 1. above, if *f* is a projective morphism from a noetherian scheme to a noetherian ring, then the higher direct image $R^{p}f_{*}{\mathcal {F}}$ is coherent.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The same result holds for proper morphisms *f*, as can be shown with the aid of Chow's lemma.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Sheaf cohomology groups *Hi* on a noetherian topological space vanish for *i* strictly greater than the dimension of the space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] is a well-defined integer (for *X* projective).
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] One can then show $\chi ({\mathcal {F}}(n))=P(n)$ for some polynomial *P* over rational numbers.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Applying this procedure to the structure sheaf ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ , one recovers the Hilbert polynomial of *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] which is manifestly intrinsic; i.e., independent of the embedding.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The arithmetic genus of a hypersurface of degree *d* is ${\binom {d-1}{n}}$ in $\mathbb {P} ^{n}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] In particular, a smooth curve of degree *d* in $\mathbb {P} ^{2}$ has arithmetic genus $(d-1)(d-2)/2$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Let *X* be a smooth projective variety where all of its irreducible components have dimension *n*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] In this situation, the canonical sheaf ω*X*, defined as the sheaf of Kähler differentials of top degree (i.e., algebraic *n*-forms), is a line bundle.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] where the superscript prime refers to the dual space and ${\mathcal {F}}^{\vee }$ is the dual sheaf of ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] A generalization to projective, but not necessarily smooth schemes is known as Verdier duality.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] For a (smooth projective) curve *X*, *H*2 and higher vanish for dimensional reason and the space of the global sections of the structure sheaf is one-dimensional.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Thus the arithmetic genus of *X* is the dimension of $H^{1}(X,{\mathcal {O}}_{X})$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] By definition, the geometric genus of *X* is the dimension of *H*0(*X*, *ω**X*).
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Serre duality thus implies that the arithmetic genus and the geometric genus coincide.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] They will simply be called the genus of *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Serre duality is also a key ingredient in the proof of the Riemann–Roch theorem.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] from the group of (Weil) divisors modulo principal divisors to the group of isomorphism classes of line bundles.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] A divisor corresponding to ω*X* is called the canonical divisor and is denoted by *K*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] A generalization of the Riemann–Roch theorem to higher dimension is the Hirzebruch–Riemann–Roch theorem, as well as the far-reaching Grothendieck–Riemann–Roch theorem.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The closed subscheme of $X\times H_{X}^{P}$ that corresponds to the identity map $H_{X}^{P}\to H_{X}^{P}$ is called the *universal family*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] For $P(z)={\binom {z+r}{r}}$ , the Hilbert scheme $H_{\mathbb {P} ^{n}}^{P}$ is called the Grassmannian of *r*-planes in $\mathbb {P} ^{n}$ and, if *X* is a projective scheme, $H_{X}^{P}$ is called the Fano scheme of *r*-planes on *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] In this section, all algebraic varieties are complex algebraic varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] A key feature of the theory of complex projective varieties is the combination of algebraic and analytic methods.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The transition between these theories is provided by the following link: since any complex polynomial is also a holomorphic function, any complex variety *X* yields a complex analytic space, denoted $X(\mathbb {C} )$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Moreover, geometric properties of *X* are reflected by the ones of $X(\mathbb {C} )$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] For example, the latter is a complex manifold if and only if *X* is smooth; it is compact if and only if *X* is proper over $\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Complex projective space is a Kähler manifold.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] This implies that, for any projective algebraic variety *X*, $X(\mathbb {C} )$ is a compact Kähler manifold.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The converse is not in general true, but the Kodaira embedding theorem gives a criterion for a Kähler manifold to be projective.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Chow's theorem provides a striking way to go the other way, from analytic to algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] It states that every analytic subvariety of a complex projective space is algebraic.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The theorem may be interpreted to saying that a holomorphic function satisfying certain growth condition is necessarily algebraic: "projective" provides this growth condition.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Chow's theorem can be shown via Serre's GAGA principle.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The complex manifold associated to an abelian variety *A* over $\mathbb {C}$ is a compact complex Lie group.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] and are also referred to as complex tori.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Here, *g* is the dimension of the torus and *L* is a lattice (also referred to as period lattice).
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] According to the uniformization theorem already mentioned above, any torus of dimension 1 arises from an abelian variety of dimension 1, i.e., from an elliptic curve.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] There is a *p*-adic analog, the p-adic uniformization theorem.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] For higher dimensions, the notions of complex abelian varieties and complex tori differ: only polarized complex tori come from abelian varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The first proof of this theorem used analytic methods of Kähler geometry, but a purely algebraic proof was found later.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] The Kodaira vanishing in general fails for a smooth projective variety in positive characteristic.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Kodaira's theorem is one of various vanishing theorems, which give criteria for higher sheaf cohomologies to vanish.
[src:algebraic-geometry/projective-variety] Since the Euler characteristic of a sheaf (see above) is often more manageable than individual cohomology groups, this often has important consequences about the geometry of projective varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Schemes elaborate the fundamental idea that an algebraic variety is best analyzed through the coordinate ring of regular algebraic functions defined on it (or on its subsets), and each subvariety corresponds to the ideal of functions which vanish on the subvariety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Intuitively, a scheme is a topological space consisting of closed points which correspond to geometric points, together with non-closed points which are generic points of irreducible subvarieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The space is covered by an atlas of open sets, each endowed with a coordinate ring of regular functions, with specified coordinate changes between the functions over intersecting open sets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Such a structure is called a ringed space or a sheaf of rings.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The cases of main interest are the Noetherian schemes, in which the coordinate rings are Noetherian rings.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Formally, a scheme is a ringed space covered by affine schemes.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] An affine scheme is the spectrum of a commutative ring; its points are the prime ideals of the ring, and its closed points are maximal ideals.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The coordinate ring of an affine scheme is the ring itself, and the coordinate rings of open subsets are rings of fractions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The relative point of view is that much of algebraic geometry should be developed for a morphism *X* → *Y* of schemes (called a scheme *X* **over the base** *Y* ), rather than for an individual scheme.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] For example, in studying algebraic surfaces, it can be useful to consider families of algebraic surfaces over any scheme *Y*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] In many cases, the family of all varieties of a given type can itself be viewed as a variety or scheme, known as a moduli space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] For some of the detailed definitions in the theory of schemes, see the glossary of scheme theory.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The origins of algebraic geometry mostly lie in the study of polynomial equations over the real numbers.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] By the 19th century, it became clear (notably in the work of Jean-Victor Poncelet and Bernhard Riemann) that algebraic geometry over the real numbers is simplified by working over the field of complex numbers, which has the advantage of being algebraically closed.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Motivated by these ideas, Emmy Noether and Wolfgang Krull developed commutative algebra in the 1920s and 1930s.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Their work generalizes algebraic geometry in a purely algebraic direction, generalizing the study of points (maximal ideals in a polynomial ring) to the study of prime ideals in any commutative ring.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] For example, Krull defined the dimension of a commutative ring in terms of prime ideals and, at least when the ring is Noetherian, he proved that this definition satisfies many of the intuitive properties of geometric dimension.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Noether and Krull's commutative algebra can be viewed as an algebraic approach to *affine* algebraic varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] However, many arguments in algebraic geometry work better for projective varieties, essentially because they are compact.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] L. van der Waerden, André Weil and Oscar Zariski applied commutative algebra as a new foundation for algebraic geometry in the richer setting of projective (or quasi-projective) varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] In particular, the Zariski topology is a useful topology on a variety over any algebraically closed field, replacing to some extent the classical topology on a complex variety (based on the metric topology of the complex numbers).
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] For applications to number theory, van der Waerden and Weil formulated algebraic geometry over any field, not necessarily algebraically closed.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Weil was the first to define an *abstract variety* (not embedded in projective space), by gluing affine varieties along open subsets, on the model of abstract manifolds in topology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] He needed this generality for his construction of the Jacobian variety of a curve over any field.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The algebraic geometers of the Italian school had often used the somewhat foggy concept of the generic point of an algebraic variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] What is true for the generic point is true for "most" points of the variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] In Weil's *Foundations of Algebraic Geometry* (1946), generic points are constructed by taking points in a very large algebraically closed field, called a *universal domain*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] This worked awkwardly: there were many different generic points for the same variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] In the 1950s, Claude Chevalley, Masayoshi Nagata and Jean-Pierre Serre, motivated in part by the Weil conjectures relating number theory and algebraic geometry, further extended the objects of algebraic geometry, for example by generalizing the base rings allowed.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The word *scheme* was first used in the 1956 Chevalley Seminar, in which Chevalley pursued Zariski's ideas.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] According to Pierre Cartier, it was André Martineau who suggested to Serre the possibility of using the spectrum of an arbitrary commutative ring as a foundation for algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The theory took its definitive form in Grothendieck's *Éléments de géométrie algébrique* (EGA) and the later *Séminaire de géométrie algébrique* (SGA), bringing to a conclusion a generation of experimental suggestions and partial developments.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] These objects $\operatorname {Spec} (R)$ are the affine schemes; a general scheme is then obtained by "gluing together" affine schemes.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Much of algebraic geometry focuses on projective or quasi-projective varieties over a field k , most often over the complex numbers.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Grothendieck developed a large body of theory for arbitrary schemes extending much of the geometric intuition for varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] For example, it is common to construct a moduli space first as a scheme, and only later study whether it is a more concrete object such as a projective variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Applying Grothendieck's theory to schemes over the integers and other number fields led to powerful new perspectives in number theory.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] An **affine scheme** is a locally ringed space isomorphic to the spectrum $\operatorname {Spec} (R)$ of a commutative ring R .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] A **scheme** is a locally ringed space X admitting a covering by open sets $U_{i}$ , such that each $U_{i}$ (as a locally ringed space) is an affine scheme.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] In particular, X comes with a sheaf ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ , which assigns to every open subset U a commutative ring ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}(U)$ called the **ring of regular functions** on U .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] One can think of a scheme as being covered by "coordinate charts" that are affine schemes.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The definition means exactly that schemes are obtained by gluing together affine schemes using the Zariski topology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] In the early days, this was called a *prescheme*, and a scheme was defined to be a separated prescheme.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The term prescheme has fallen out of use, but can still be found in older books, such as Grothendieck's "Éléments de géométrie algébrique" and Mumford's "Red Book".
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The sheaf properties of ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}(U)$ mean that its elements*,* which are not necessarily functions, can nevertheless be patched together from their restrictions in the same way as functions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] A basic example of an affine scheme is **affine n -space** over a field k , for a natural number n .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] By definition, $A_{k}^{n}$ is the spectrum of the polynomial ring $k[x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}]$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] In the spirit of scheme theory, affine n -space can in fact be defined over any commutative ring R , meaning $\operatorname {Spec} (R[x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}])$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Schemes form a category, with morphisms defined as morphisms of locally ringed spaces.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] (See also: morphism of schemes.) For a scheme *Y*, a scheme *X* **over** *Y* (or a *Y*-**scheme**) means a morphism *X* → *Y* of schemes.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] A scheme *X* **over** a commutative ring *R* means a morphism *X* → Spec(*R*).
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] An algebraic variety over a field *k* can be defined as a scheme over *k* with certain properties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] There are different conventions about exactly which schemes should be called varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] One standard choice is that a **variety** over *k* means an integral separated scheme of finite type over *k*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] A morphism *f*: *X* → *Y* of schemes determines a **pullback homomorphism** on the rings of regular functions, *f**: *O*(*Y*) → *O*(*X*).
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] In the case of affine schemes, this construction gives a one-to-one correspondence between morphisms Spec(*A*) → Spec(*B*) of schemes and ring homomorphisms *B* → *A*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] In this sense, scheme theory completely subsumes the theory of commutative rings.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Since **Z** is an initial object in the category of commutative rings, the category of schemes has Spec(**Z**) as a terminal object.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] For a scheme *X* over a commutative ring *R*, an *R*-**point** of *X* means a section of the morphism *X* → Spec(*R*).
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] One writes *X*(*R*) for the set of *R*-points of *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] In examples, this definition reconstructs the old notion of the set of solutions of the defining equations of *X* with values in *R*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] When *R* is a field *k*, *X*(*k*) is also called the set of *k*-rational points of *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] More generally, for a scheme *X* over a commutative ring *R* and any commutative *R*-algebra *S*, an *S*-**point** of *X* means a morphism Spec(*S*) → *X* over *R*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] One writes *X*(*S*) for the set of *S*-points of *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] (This generalizes the old observation that given some equations over a field *k*, one can consider the set of solutions of the equations in any field extension *E* of *k*.) For a scheme *X* over *R*, the assignment *S* ↦ *X*(*S*) is a functor from commutative *R*-algebras to sets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] It is an important observation that a scheme *X* over *R* is determined by this functor of points.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The fiber product of schemes always exists.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] That is, for any schemes *X* and *Z* with morphisms to a scheme *Y*, the categorical fiber product $X\times _{Y}Z$ exists in the category of schemes.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] If *X* and *Z* are schemes over a field *k*, their fiber product over Spec(*k*) may be called the **product** *X* × *Z* in the category of *k*-schemes.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] For example, the product of affine spaces $\mathbb {A} ^{m}$ and $\mathbb {A} ^{n}$ over *k* is affine space $\mathbb {A} ^{m+n}$ over *k*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Since the category of schemes has fiber products and also a terminal object Spec(**Z**), it has all finite limits.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Here and below, all the rings considered are commutative.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The affine space ${\bar {X}}=\mathbb {A} _{k}^{n}$ is the algebraic variety of all points $a=(a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n})$ with coordinates in k; its coordinate ring is the polynomial ring $R=k[x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}]$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The corresponding scheme $X=\mathrm {Spec} (R)$ is a topological space with the Zariski topology, whose closed points are the maximal ideals ${\mathfrak {m}}_{a}=(x_{1}-a_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}-a_{n})$ , the set of polynomials vanishing at a .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The closed subscheme has coordinate ring $R/{\mathfrak {p}}$ : that is $V({\mathfrak {p}})\cong \mathop {\rm {Spec}} (R/{\mathfrak {p}})$ , since prime ideals ${\bar {\mathfrak {q}}}\subset R/{\mathfrak {p}}$ are in natural bijection with ${\mathfrak {p}}\subset {\mathfrak {q}}\subset R$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The scheme X has a basis of open subsets given by the complements of hypersurfaces, $U_{f}=X\setminus V(f)=\{{\mathfrak {p}}\in X\ \ {\text{with}}\ \ f\notin {\mathfrak {p}}\}$ for irreducible polynomials $f\in R$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Each ring element $g=g(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})\in R$ , a polynomial function on ${\bar {X}}$ , also defines a function on the points of the scheme X whose value at ${\mathfrak {p}}$ lies in the quotient ring $R/{\mathfrak {p}}$ , the *residue ring*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] We define $g({\mathfrak {p}})$ as the image of g under the natural map $R\to R/{\mathfrak {p}}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] A maximal ideal ${\mathfrak {m}}_{a}$ gives the *residue field* $k({\mathfrak {m}}_{a})=R/{\mathfrak {m}}_{a}\cong k$ , with the natural isomorphism $x_{i}\mapsto a_{i}$ , so that $g({\mathfrak {m}}_{a})$ corresponds to the original value $g(a)$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The vanishing locus of a polynomial $f=f(x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n})$ is a hypersurface subvariety ${\bar {V}}(f)\subset \mathbb {A} _{k}^{n}$ , also called a divisor, corresponding to the principal ideal $(f)\subset R$ with corresponding closed subscheme ${\textstyle V(f)=\operatorname {Spec} (R/(f))}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] For example, taking k to be the complex or real numbers, the equation $x^{2}=y^{2}(y+1)$ defines a nodal cubic curve in the affine plane $\mathbb {A} _{k}^{2}$ , corresponding to the scheme $V=\operatorname {Spec} k[x,y]/(x^{2}-y^{2}(y+1))$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The ring of integers $\mathbb {Z}$ can be considered as the coordinate ring of the scheme $Z=\operatorname {Spec} (\mathbb {Z} )$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The Zariski topology has closed points ${\mathfrak {m}}_{p}=(p)$ , the principal ideals of the prime numbers $p\in \mathbb {Z}$ ; as well as the generic point ${\mathfrak {p}}_{0}=(0)$ , the zero ideal, whose closure is the whole scheme.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Closed sets are finite sets, and open sets are their complements, the cofinite sets; any infinite set of points is dense.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The function n is determined by its values at the points ${\mathfrak {m}}_{p}$ only, so we can think of n as a kind of "regular function" on the closed points, a very special type among the arbitrary functions f with $f({\mathfrak {m}}_{p})\in \mathbb {F} _{p}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Note that the point ${\mathfrak {m}}_{p}$ is the vanishing locus of the function $n=p$ , the point where the value of p is equal to zero in the residue field.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The field of "rational functions" on Z is the fraction field of the generic residue ring, $k({\mathfrak {p}}_{0})=\operatorname {Frac} (\mathbb {Z} )=\mathbb {Q}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] A fraction $a/b$ has "poles" at the points ${\mathfrak {m}}_{p}$ corresponding to prime divisors of the denominator.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] This also gives a geometric interpretation of Bézout's lemma stating that if the integers $n_{1},\ldots ,n_{r}$ have no common prime factor, then there are integers $a_{1},\ldots ,a_{r}$ with $a_{1}n_{1}+\cdots +a_{r}n_{r}=1$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Geometrically, this is a version of the weak Hilbert Nullstellensatz for the scheme Z : if the functions $n_{1},\ldots ,n_{r}$ have no common vanishing points ${\mathfrak {m}}_{p}$ in Z , then they generate the unit ideal $(n_{1},\ldots ,n_{r})=(1)$ in the coordinate ring $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Indeed, we may consider the terms $\rho _{i}=a_{i}n_{i}$ as forming a kind of partition of unity subordinate to the covering of Z by the open sets $U_{i}=Z\smallsetminus V(n_{i})$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The affine space $\mathbb {A} _{\mathbb {Z} }^{1}=\{a\ {\text{for}}\ a\in \mathbb {Z} \}$ is a variety with coordinate ring $\mathbb {Z} [x]$ , the polynomials with integer coefficients.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The corresponding scheme is $Y=\operatorname {Spec} (\mathbb {Z} [x])$ , whose points are all of the prime ideals ${\mathfrak {p}}\subset \mathbb {Z} [x]$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The closed points are maximal ideals of the form ${\mathfrak {m}}=(p,f(x))$ , where p is a prime number, and $f(x)$ is a non-constant polynomial with no integer factor and which is irreducible modulo p .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Thus, we may picture Y as two-dimensional, with a "characteristic direction" measured by the coordinate p , and a "spatial direction" with coordinate x .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] There is no corresponding "x-axis" projection, since for example the "horizontal lines" $x=a$ and $x=b$ , the subschemes $V(x-a)$ and $V(x-b)$ , intersect each other wherever $a\equiv b\!\!\!\!\mod p$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] We also have the "diagonal line" $V(bx-a)$ corresponding to the rational coordinate $x=a/b$ , which does not intersect $V(p)$ for those p which divide b .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The fiber over $(p)$ consists of x -values which are roots of $x^{2}+1$ modulo p , which may split, ramify, or remain inert.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Overall, $V(x^{2}+1)$ is a curve of degree 2, having in some sense a double fiber over each $(p)$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Not all finite extensions of the integers appear in this way as quotients of $\mathbb {Z} [x]$ , only those which are generated by a single element.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] A polynomial $g(x)\in \mathbb {Z} [x]$ corresponds to a function on the scheme Y with values $g({\mathfrak {m}})=g\ \mathrm {mod} \ {\mathfrak {m}}$ , that is $g({\mathfrak {m}})=g(\alpha )\in \mathbb {F} _{p}(\alpha )$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Again each $g(x)\in \mathbb {Z} [x]$ is determined by its values $g({\mathfrak {m}})$ at closed points, and $V(p)$ is the vanishing locus of the constant polynomial $g(x)=p$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The closed subscheme $V(f(x))$ contains the points in each characteristic p corresponding to Galois orbits of roots of $f(x)$ in the algebraic closure ${\overline {\mathbb {F} }}_{p}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The scheme $Y=\operatorname {Spec} (\mathbb {Z} [x])$ is not proper, so that pairs of curves may fail to intersect with the expected multiplicity.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] This is a major obstacle to analyzing Diophantine equations with geometric tools.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Arakelov theory overcomes this obstacle by compactifying affine arithmetic schemes, adding points at infinity corresponding to Archimedean valuations.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] If we consider a polynomial $f\in \mathbb {Z} [x,y]$ then the affine scheme $X=\operatorname {Spec} (\mathbb {Z} [x,y]/(f))$ has a canonical morphism to $\operatorname {Spec} \mathbb {Z}$ and is called an arithmetic surface.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The fibers $X_{p}=X\times _{\operatorname {Spec} (\mathbb {Z} )}\operatorname {Spec} (\mathbb {F} _{p})$ are then algebraic curves over the finite fields $\mathbb {F} _{p}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] This curve is singular over the prime numbers $3,p$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] It is also fruitful to consider examples of morphisms as examples of schemes since they demonstrate their technical effectiveness for encapsulating many objects of study in algebraic and arithmetic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Here are some of the ways in which schemes go beyond older notions of algebraic varieties, and their significance.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] A central part of scheme theory is the notion of coherent sheaves, generalizing the notion of (algebraic) vector bundles.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] For a scheme *X*, one starts by considering the abelian category of ***O**X*-modules**, which are sheaves of abelian groups on *X* that form a module over the sheaf of regular functions *O**X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] In particular, a module *M* over a commutative ring *R* determines an associated *O**X*-module ~*M* on *X* = Spec(*R*).
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] A **quasi-coherent sheaf** on a scheme *X* means an *O**X*-module that is the sheaf associated to a module on each affine open subset of *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Finally, a **coherent sheaf** (on a Noetherian scheme *X*, say) is an *O**X*-module that is the sheaf associated to a finitely generated module on each affine open subset of *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Coherent sheaves include the important class of **vector bundles**, which are the sheaves that locally come from finitely generated free modules.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] An example is the tangent bundle of a smooth variety over a field.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] However, coherent sheaves are richer; for example, a vector bundle on a closed subscheme *Y* of *X* can be viewed as a coherent sheaf on *X* that is zero outside *Y* (by the direct image construction).
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] In this way, coherent sheaves on a scheme *X* include information about all closed subschemes of *X*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Moreover, sheaf cohomology has good properties for coherent (and quasi-coherent) sheaves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The resulting theory of coherent sheaf cohomology is perhaps the main technical tool in algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Considered as its functor of points, a scheme is a functor that is a sheaf of sets for the Zariski topology on the category of commutative rings, and that, locally in the Zariski topology, is an affine scheme.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] This can be generalized in several ways.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Michael Artin defined an **algebraic space** as a functor that is a sheaf in the étale topology and that, locally in the étale topology, is an affine scheme.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Equivalently, an algebraic space is the quotient of a scheme by an étale equivalence relation.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] A powerful result, the Artin representability theorem, gives simple conditions for a functor to be represented by an algebraic space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] A further generalization is the idea of a stack.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Crudely speaking, **algebraic stacks** generalize algebraic spaces by having an algebraic group attached to each point, which is viewed as the automorphism group of that point.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] For example, any action of an algebraic group *G* on an algebraic variety *X* determines a **quotient stack** [*X*/*G*], which remembers the stabilizer subgroups for the action of *G*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] More generally, moduli spaces in algebraic geometry are often best viewed as stacks, thereby keeping track of the automorphism groups of the objects being classified.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Grothendieck originally introduced stacks as a tool for the theory of descent.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] In that formulation, stacks are (informally speaking) sheaves of categories.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] From this general notion, Artin defined the narrower class of algebraic stacks (or "Artin stacks"), which can be considered geometric objects.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] These include Deligne–Mumford stacks (similar to orbifolds in topology), for which the stabilizer groups are finite, and algebraic spaces, for which the stabilizer groups are trivial.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] The Keel–Mori theorem says that an algebraic stack with finite stabilizer groups has a coarse moduli space that is an algebraic space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Another type of generalization is to enrich the structure sheaf, bringing algebraic geometry closer to homotopy theory.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] In this setting, known as derived algebraic geometry or "spectral algebraic geometry", the structure sheaf is replaced by a homotopical analog of a sheaf of commutative rings (for example, a sheaf of E-infinity ring spectra).
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] These sheaves admit algebraic operations that are associative and commutative only up to an equivalence relation.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Taking the quotient by this equivalence relation yields the structure sheaf of an ordinary scheme.
[src:algebraic-geometry/scheme-mathematics] Not taking the quotient, however, leads to a theory that can remember higher information, in the same way that derived functors in homological algebra yield higher information about operations such as tensor product and the Hom functor on modules.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In mathematics, a **sheaf** (pl.: **sheaves**) is a tool for systematically tracking data (such as sets, abelian groups, rings) attached to the open sets of a topological space and defined locally with regard to them.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, for each open set, the data could be the ring of continuous functions defined on that open set.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The field of mathematics that studies sheaves is called **sheaf theory**.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Sheaves are understood conceptually as general and abstract objects.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Their precise definition is rather technical.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] They are specifically defined as **sheaves of sets** or as **sheaves of rings**, for example, depending on the type of data assigned to the open sets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] There are also maps (or morphisms) from one sheaf to another; sheaves (of a specific type, such as sheaves of abelian groups) with their morphisms on a fixed topological space form a category.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] On the other hand, to each continuous map there is associated both a direct image functor, taking sheaves and their morphisms on the domain to sheaves and morphisms on the codomain, and an inverse image functor operating in the opposite direction.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] These functors, and certain variants of them, are essential parts of sheaf theory.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Due to their general nature and versatility, sheaves have several applications in topology and especially in algebraic and differential geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] First, geometric structures such as that of a differentiable manifold or a scheme can be expressed in terms of a sheaf of rings on the space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In such contexts, several geometric constructions such as vector bundles or divisors are naturally specified in terms of sheaves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Second, sheaves provide the framework for a very general cohomology theory, which encompasses also the "usual" topological cohomology theories such as singular cohomology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Especially in algebraic geometry and the theory of complex manifolds, sheaf cohomology provides a powerful link between topological and geometric properties of spaces.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Sheaves also provide the basis for the theory of *D*-modules, which provide applications to the theory of differential equations.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In addition, generalisations of sheaves to more general settings than topological spaces, such as the notion of a sheaf on a category with respect to some Grothendieck topology, have provided applications to mathematical logic and to number theory.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The ability to restrict data to smaller open subsets gives rise to the concept of presheaves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Roughly speaking, sheaves are then those presheaves, where local data can be glued to global data.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Informally, the second axiom says it does not matter whether we restrict to W in one step or restrict first to V , then to W .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A concise functorial reformulation of this definition is given further below.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Many examples of presheaves come from different classes of functions: to any U , one can assign the set $C^{0}(U)$ of continuous real-valued functions on U .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The restriction maps are then just given by restricting a continuous function on U to a smaller open subset $V\subseteq U$ , which again is a continuous function.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The two presheaf axioms are immediately checked, thereby giving an example of a presheaf.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This can be extended to a presheaf of holomorphic functions ${\mathcal {H}}(-)$ and a presheaf of smooth functions $C^{\infty }(-)$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Another common class of examples is assigning to U the set of constant real-valued functions on U .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This presheaf is called the *constant presheaf* associated to $\mathbb {R}$ and is denoted ${\underline {\mathbb {R} }}^{\text{psh}}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Given a presheaf, a natural question to ask is to what extent its sections over an open set U are specified by their restrictions to open subsets of U .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A *sheaf* is a presheaf whose sections are, in a technical sense, uniquely determined by their restrictions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] (*Gluing*) Suppose U is an open set, $\{U_{i}\}_{i\in I}$ is an open cover of U with $U_{i}\subseteq U$ for all $i\in I$ , and $\{s_{i}\in {\mathcal {F}}(U_{i})\}_{i\in I}$ is a family of sections.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] If all pairs of sections agree on the overlap of their domains, that is, if $s_{i}|_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}}=s_{j}|_{U_{i}\cap U_{j}}$ for all $i,j\in I$ , then there exists a section $s\in {\mathcal {F}}(U)$ such that $s|_{U_{i}}=s_{i}$ for all $i\in I$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In both of these axioms, the hypothesis on the open cover is equivalent to the assumption that ${\textstyle \bigcup _{i\in I}U_{i}=U}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The section s whose existence is guaranteed by axiom 2 is called the *gluing*, *concatenation*, or *collation* of the sections $s_{i}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Sections $s_{i}$ and $s_{j}$ satisfying the agreement precondition of axiom 2 are often called *compatible* ; thus axioms 1 and 2 together state that *any collection of pairwise compatible sections can be uniquely glued together*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A *separated presheaf*, or *monopresheaf*, is a presheaf satisfying axiom 1.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The presheaf consisting of continuous functions mentioned above is a sheaf.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This assertion reduces to checking that, given continuous functions $f_{i}:U_{i}\to \mathbb {R}$ which agree on the intersections $U_{i}\cap U_{j}$ , there is a unique continuous function $f:U\to \mathbb {R}$ whose restriction equals the $f_{i}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] By contrast, the constant presheaf is usually *not* a sheaf as it fails to satisfy the locality axiom on the empty set (this is explained in more detail at constant sheaf).
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Presheaves and sheaves are typically denoted by capital letters, F being particularly common, presumably for the French word for sheaf, *faisceau*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Use of calligraphic letters such as ${\mathcal {F}}$ is also common.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It can be shown that to specify a sheaf, it is enough to specify its restriction to the open sets of a basis for the topology of the underlying space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Moreover, it can also be shown that it is enough to verify the sheaf axioms above relative to the open sets of a covering.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This observation is used to construct another example which is crucial in algebraic geometry, namely quasi-coherent sheaves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Here the topological space in question is the spectrum of a commutative ring R , whose points are the prime ideals ${\mathfrak {p}}$ in R .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The open sets $D_{f}:=\{{\mathfrak {p}}\subseteq R,f\notin {\mathfrak {p}}\}$ form a basis for the Zariski topology on this space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Given an R -module M , there is a sheaf, denoted by ${\tilde {M}}$ on the $\operatorname {Spec} R$ , that satisfies ${\tilde {M}}(D_{f}):=M[1/f],$ where $M[1/f]$ is the localization of M at f .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] There is another characterization of sheaves that is equivalent to the previously discussed.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This characterization is useful in construction of sheaves, for example, if ${\mathcal {F}},{\mathcal {G}}$ are abelian sheaves, then the kernel of sheaves morphism ${\mathcal {F}}\to {\mathcal {G}}$ is a sheaf, since projective limits commute with projective limits.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] On the other hand, the cokernel is not always a sheaf because inductive limits do not necessarily commute with projective limits.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] One way to fix this is to consider Noetherian topological spaces; all open sets are compact so that the cokernel is a sheaf, since finite projective limits commute with inductive limits.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Any such s is commonly called a section of f , and this example is the reason why the elements in ${\mathcal {F}}(U)$ are generally called sections.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This construction is especially important when f is the projection of a fiber bundle onto its base space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, the sheaves of smooth functions are the sheaves of sections of the trivial bundle.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] is the sheaf which assigns to any $U\subseteq \mathbb {C} \setminus \{0\}$ the set of branches of the complex logarithm on U .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Given a point x and an abelian group S , the skyscraper sheaf $S_{x}$ is defined as follows: if U is an open set containing x , then $S_{x}(U)=S$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] If U does not contain x , then $S_{x}(U)=0$ , the trivial group.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The restriction maps are either the identity on S , if both open sets contain x , or the zero map otherwise.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] On an n -dimensional $C^{k}$ -manifold M , there are a number of important sheaves, such as the sheaf of j -times continuously differentiable functions ${\mathcal {O}}_{M}^{j}$ (with $j\leq k$ ).
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Its sections on some open U are the $C^{j}$ -functions $U\to \mathbb {R}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For $j=k$ , this sheaf is called the *structure sheaf* and is denoted ${\mathcal {O}}_{M}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The nonzero $C^{k}$ functions also form a sheaf, denoted ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}^{\times }$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Differential forms (of degree p ) also form a sheaf $\Omega _{M}^{p}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In all these examples, the restriction morphisms are given by restricting functions or forms.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The assignment sending U to the compactly supported functions on U is not a sheaf, since there is, in general, no way to preserve this property by passing to a smaller open subset.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Instead, this forms a cosheaf, a dual concept where the restriction maps go in the opposite direction than with sheaves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] However, taking the dual of these vector spaces does give a sheaf, the sheaf of distributions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] One of the historical motivations for sheaves have come from studying complex manifolds, complex analytic geometry, and scheme theory from algebraic geometry.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This is because in all of the previous cases, we consider a topological space X together with a structure sheaf ${\mathcal {O}}$ giving it the structure of a complex manifold, complex analytic space, or scheme.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This perspective of equipping a topological space with a sheaf is essential to the theory of locally ringed spaces (see below).
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] One of the main historical motivations for introducing sheaves was constructing a device which keeps track of holomorphic functions on complex manifolds.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This means there exist two compact complex manifolds $X,X'$ which are not isomorphic, but nevertheless their rings of global holomorphic functions, denoted ${\mathcal {H}}(X),{\mathcal {H}}(X')$ , are isomorphic.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Contrast this with smooth manifolds where every manifold M can be embedded inside some $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , hence its ring of smooth functions $C^{\infty }(M)$ comes from restricting the smooth functions from $C^{\infty }(\mathbb {R} ^{n})$ , of which there exist plenty.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Another complexity when considering the ring of holomorphic functions on a complex manifold X is given a small enough open set $U\subseteq X$ , the holomorphic functions will be isomorphic to ${\mathcal {H}}(U)\cong {\mathcal {H}}(\mathbb {C} ^{n})$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Sheaves are a direct tool for dealing with this complexity since they make it possible to keep track of the holomorphic structure on the underlying topological space of X on arbitrary open subsets $U\subseteq X$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This means as U becomes more complex topologically, the ring ${\mathcal {H}}(U)$ can be expressed from gluing the ${\mathcal {H}}(U_{i})$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Note that sometimes this sheaf is denoted ${\mathcal {O}}(-)$ or just ${\mathcal {O}}$ , or even ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ when we want to emphasize the space the structure sheaf is associated to.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Another common example of sheaves can be constructed by considering a complex submanifold $Y\hookrightarrow X$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] There is an associated sheaf ${\mathcal {O}}_{Y}$ which takes an open subset $U\subseteq X$ and gives the ring of holomorphic functions on $U\cap Y$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This kind of formalism was found to be extremely powerful and motivates a lot of homological algebra such as sheaf cohomology since an intersection theory can be built using these kinds of sheaves from the Serre intersection formula.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Morphisms of sheaves are, roughly speaking, analogous to functions between them.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In contrast to a function between sets, which is simply an assignment of outputs to inputs, morphisms of sheaves are also required to be compatible with the local–global structures of the underlying sheaves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This idea is made precise in the following definition.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Let ${\mathcal {F}}$ and ${\mathcal {G}}$ be two sheaves of sets (respectively abelian groups, rings, etc.) on X .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A *morphism* $\varphi :{\mathcal {F}}\to {\mathcal {G}}$ consists of a morphism $\varphi _{U}:{\mathcal {F}}(U)\to {\mathcal {G}}(U)$ of sets (respectively abelian groups, rings, etc.) for each open set U of X , subject to the condition that this morphism is compatible with restrictions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In other words, for every open subset V of an open set U , the following diagram is commutative.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Indeed, given an ( n -times continuously differentiable) function $f:U\to \mathbb {R}$ (with U in $\mathbb {R}$ open), the restriction (to a smaller open subset V ) of its derivative equals the derivative of $f|_{V}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] With this notion of morphism, sheaves of sets (respectively abelian groups, rings, etc.) on a fixed topological space X form a category.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The general categorical notions of mono-, epi- and isomorphisms can therefore be applied to sheaves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] These statements give examples of how to work with sheaves using local information, but it's important to note that we cannot check if a morphism of sheaves is an epimorphism in the same manner.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Indeed the statement that maps on the level of open sets $\varphi _{U}\colon {\mathcal {F}}(U)\rightarrow {\mathcal {G}}(U)$ are not always surjective for epimorphisms of sheaves is equivalent to non-exactness of the global sections functor—or equivalently, to non-triviality of sheaf cohomology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The *stalk* ${\mathcal {F}}_{x}$ of a sheaf ${\mathcal {F}}$ captures the properties of a sheaf "around" a point $x\in X$ , generalizing the germs of functions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Here, "around" means that, conceptually speaking, one looks at smaller and smaller neighborhoods of the point.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Of course, no single neighborhood will be small enough, which requires considering a limit of some sort.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] the direct limit being over all open subsets of X containing the given point x .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In other words, an element of the stalk is given by a section over some open neighborhood of x , and two such sections are considered equivalent if their restrictions agree on a smaller neighborhood.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The natural morphism ${\mathcal {F}}(U)\to {\mathcal {F}}_{x}$ takes a section s in ${\mathcal {F}}(U)$ to its *germ* $s_{x}$ at x .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This generalises the usual definition of a germ.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In many situations, knowing the stalks of a sheaf is enough to control the sheaf itself.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, whether or not a morphism of sheaves is a monomorphism, epimorphism, or isomorphism can be tested on the stalks.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In this sense, a sheaf is determined by its stalks, which are a local data.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] By contrast, the *global* information present in a sheaf, i.e., the *global sections*, i.e., the sections ${\mathcal {F}}(X)$ on the whole space X , typically carry less information.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, for a compact complex manifold X , the global sections of the sheaf of holomorphic functions are just $\mathbb {C}$ , since any holomorphic function $X\to \mathbb {C}$ is constant by Liouville's theorem.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It is frequently useful to take the data contained in a presheaf and to express it as a sheaf.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It turns out that there is a best possible way to do this.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It takes a presheaf ${\mathcal {F}}$ and produces a new sheaf $a{\mathcal {F}}$ called the *sheafification* or *sheaf associated to the presheaf* ${\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, the sheafification of the constant presheaf (see above) is called the *constant sheaf*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Despite its name, its sections are *locally* constant functions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The associated sheaf $a{\mathcal {F}}$ is given by $LL{\mathcal {F}}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In fact, a is the left adjoint functor to the inclusion functor (or forgetful functor) from the category of sheaves to the category of presheaves, and i is the unit of the adjunction.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In this way, the category of sheaves turns into a Giraud subcategory of presheaves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This categorical situation is the reason why the sheafification functor appears in constructing cokernels of sheaf morphisms or tensor products of sheaves, but not for kernels, say.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The set $\operatorname {Hom} (F,G)$ of morphisms of sheaves from F to G forms an abelian group (by the abelian group structure of G ).
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] is the sheaf of abelian groups $U\mapsto \operatorname {Hom} (F|_{U},G|_{U})$ where $F|_{U}$ is the sheaf on U given by $(F|_{U})(V)=F(V)$ (note sheafification is not needed here).
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The direct sum of F and G is the sheaf given by $U\mapsto F(U)\oplus G(U)$ , and the tensor product of F and G is the sheaf associated to the presheaf $U\mapsto F(U)\otimes G(U)$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] All of these operations extend to sheaves of modules over a sheaf of rings A ; the above is the special case when A is the constant sheaf ${\underline {\mathbf {Z} }}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Since the data of a (pre-)sheaf depends on the open subsets of the base space, sheaves on different topological spaces are unrelated to each other in the sense that there are no morphisms between them.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] However, given a continuous map $f:X\to Y$ between two topological spaces, pushforward and pullback relate sheaves on X to those on Y and vice versa.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Here V is an open subset of Y , so that its preimage is open in X by the continuity of f .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] where $i:\{x\}\to X$ is the inclusion, and S is regarded as a sheaf on the singleton by $S(\{*\})=S,S(\emptyset )=\emptyset$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For a map between locally compact spaces, the direct image with compact support is a subsheaf of the direct image.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] By definition, $(f_{!}{\mathcal {F}})(V)$ consists of those $s\in {\mathcal {F}}(f^{-1}(V))$ whose support is mapped properly.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] If f is proper itself, then $f_{!}{\mathcal {F}}=f_{*}{\mathcal {F}}$ , but in general they disagree.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The pullback or inverse image goes the other way: it produces a sheaf on X , denoted $f^{-1}{\mathcal {G}}$ out of a sheaf ${\mathcal {G}}$ on Y .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] If f is the inclusion of an open subset, then the inverse image is just a restriction, i.e., it is given by $(f^{-1}{\mathcal {G}})(U)={\mathcal {G}}(U)$ for an open U in X .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A sheaf ${\mathcal {F}}$ (on some space X ) is called locally constant if $X=\bigcup _{i\in I}U_{i}$ by some open subsets $U_{i}$ such that the restriction of ${\mathcal {F}}$ to all these open subsets is constant.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] On a wide range of topological spaces X , such sheaves are equivalent to representations of the fundamental group $\pi _{1}(X)$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For general maps f , the definition of $f^{-1}{\mathcal {G}}$ is more involved; it is detailed at inverse image functor.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] More generally, if $A\subset X$ is a locally closed subset, then there exists an open U of X containing A such that A is closed in U .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Let $f:A\to U$ and $j:U\to X$ be the natural inclusions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Then the *extension by zero* of a sheaf ${\mathcal {F}}$ on A is defined by $j_{!}f_{*}F$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Due to its nice behavior on stalks, the extension by zero functor is useful for reducing sheaf-theoretic questions on X to ones on the strata of a stratification, i.e., a decomposition of X into smaller, locally closed subsets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In addition to (pre-)sheaves as introduced above, where ${\mathcal {F}}(U)$ is merely a set, it is in many cases important to keep track of additional structure on these sections.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, the sections of the sheaf of continuous functions naturally form a real vector space, and restriction is a linear map between these vector spaces.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Presheaves with values in an arbitrary category C are defined by first considering the category of open sets on X to be the posetal category $O(X)$ whose objects are the open sets of X and whose morphisms are inclusions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Then a C -valued presheaf on X is the same as a contravariant functor from $O(X)$ to C .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Morphisms in this category of functors, also known as natural transformations, are the same as the morphisms defined above, as can be seen by unraveling the definitions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A particular case of this sheaf condition occurs for U being the empty set, and the index set I also being empty.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In this case, the sheaf condition requires ${\mathcal {F}}(\emptyset )$ to be the terminal object in C .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In several geometrical disciplines, including algebraic geometry and differential geometry, the spaces come along with a natural sheaf of rings, often called the structure sheaf and denoted by ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Such a pair $(X,{\mathcal {O}}_{X})$ is called a *ringed space*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Many types of spaces can be defined as certain types of ringed spaces.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Commonly, all the stalks ${\mathcal {O}}_{X,x}$ of the structure sheaf are local rings, in which case the pair is called a *locally ringed space*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, an n -dimensional $C^{k}$ manifold M is a locally ringed space whose structure sheaf consists of $C^{k}$ -functions on the open subsets of M .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The property of being a *locally* ringed space translates into the fact that such a function, which is nonzero at a point x , is also non-zero on a sufficiently small open neighborhood of x .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Some authors actually *define* real (or complex) manifolds to be locally ringed spaces that are locally isomorphic to the pair consisting of an open subset of $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ (respectively $\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ ) together with the sheaf of $C^{k}$ (respectively holomorphic) functions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Similarly, schemes, the foundational notion of spaces in algebraic geometry, are locally ringed spaces that are locally isomorphic to the spectrum of a ring.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Most important geometric objects are sheaves of modules.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, there is a one-to-one correspondence between vector bundles and locally free sheaves of ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ -modules.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This paradigm applies to real vector bundles, complex vector bundles, or vector bundles in algebraic geometry (where ${\mathcal {O}}$ consists of smooth functions, holomorphic functions, or regular functions, respectively).
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Sheaves of solutions to differential equations are D -modules, that is, modules over the sheaf of differential operators.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] On any topological space, modules over the constant sheaf ${\underline {\mathbf {Z} }}$ are the same as sheaves of abelian groups in the sense above.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] There is a different inverse image functor for sheaves of modules over sheaves of rings.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This functor is usually denoted $f^{*}$ and it is distinct from $f^{-1}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Like for modules, coherence is in general a strictly stronger condition than finite presentation.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The Oka coherence theorem states that the sheaf of holomorphic functions on a complex manifold is coherent.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In the examples above it was noted that some sheaves occur naturally as sheaves of sections.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In fact, all sheaves of sets can be represented as sheaves of sections of a topological space called the *étalé space*, from the French word French pronunciation: [étalé], meaning roughly "spread out".
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] If $F\in {\text{Sh}}(X)$ is a sheaf over X , then the **étalé space** (sometimes called the **étale space**) of F is a topological space E together with a local homeomorphism $\pi :E\to X$ such that the sheaf of sections $\Gamma (\pi ,-)$ of $\pi$ is F .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The space E is usually very strange, and even if the sheaf F arises from a natural topological situation, E may not have any clear topological interpretation.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, if F is the sheaf of sections of a continuous function $f:Y\to X$ , then $E=Y$ if and only if f is a local homeomorphism.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The étalé space E is constructed from the stalks of F over X .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] As a set, it is their disjoint union and $\pi$ is the obvious map that takes the value x on the stalk of F over $x\in X$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The topology of E is defined as follows.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For each element $s\in F(U)$ and each $x\in U$ , we get a germ of s at x , denoted $[s]_{x}$ or $s_{x}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For any U and $s\in F(U)$ , the union of these points (for all $x\in U$ ) is declared to be open in E .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Notice that each stalk has the discrete topology as subspace topology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A morphism between two sheaves determine a continuous map of the corresponding étalé spaces that is compatible with the projection maps (in the sense that every germ is mapped to a germ over the same point).
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This makes the construction into a functor.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The construction above determines an equivalence of categories between the category of sheaves of sets on X and the category of étalé spaces over X .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The construction of an étalé space can also be applied to a presheaf, in which case the sheaf of sections of the étalé space recovers the sheaf associated to the given presheaf.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This construction makes all sheaves into representable functors on certain categories of topological spaces.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] As above, let F be a sheaf on X , let E be its étalé space, and let $\pi :E\to X$ be the natural projection.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Consider the overcategory ${\text{Top}}/X$ of topological spaces over X , that is, the category of topological spaces together with fixed continuous maps to X .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Every object of this category is a continuous map $f:Y\to X$ , and a morphism from $Y\to X$ to $Z\to X$ is a continuous map $Y\to Z$ that commutes with the two maps to X .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] which shows that $\pi :E\to X$ (for the étalé space) represents the functor $\Gamma$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] E is constructed so that the projection map $\pi$ is a covering map.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In algebraic geometry, the natural analog of a covering map is called an étale morphism.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Despite its similarity to "étalé", the word étale [etal] has a different meaning in French.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It is possible to turn E into a scheme and $\pi$ into a morphism of schemes in such a way that $\pi$ retains the same universal property, but $\pi$ is *not* in general an étale morphism because it is not quasi-finite.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The definition of sheaves by étalé spaces is older than the definition given earlier in the article.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It is still common in some areas of mathematics such as mathematical analysis.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] As was noted above, this functor does not preserve epimorphisms.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] of open subsets, such that the restriction $g|_{U_{i}}$ are in the image of ${\mathcal {F}}(U_{i})$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] However, g itself need not be in the image of ${\mathcal {F}}(U)$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] ${\mathcal {O}}{\stackrel {\exp }{\to }}{\mathcal {O}}^{\times }$ between the sheaf of holomorphic functions and non-zero holomorphic functions.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This map is an epimorphism, which amounts to saying that any non-zero holomorphic function g (on some open subset in $\mathbb {C}$ , say), admits a complex logarithm *locally*, i.e., after restricting g to appropriate open subsets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] However, g need not have a logarithm globally.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Sheaf cohomology captures this phenomenon.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] There are several different ways of constructing sheaf cohomology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Grothendieck (1957) introduced them by defining sheaf cohomology as the derived functor of $\Gamma$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This method is theoretically satisfactory, but, being based on injective resolutions, of little use in concrete computations.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Godement resolutions are another general, but practically inaccessible approach.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Especially in the context of sheaves on manifolds, sheaf cohomology can often be computed using resolutions by soft sheaves, fine sheaves, and flabby sheaves (also known as ***flasque sheaves*** from the French *flasque* meaning flabby).
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, a partition of unity argument shows that the sheaf of smooth functions on a manifold is soft.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The higher cohomology groups $H^{i}(U,{\mathcal {F}})$ for $i>0$ vanish for soft sheaves, which gives a way of computing cohomology of other sheaves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, the de Rham complex is a resolution of the constant sheaf ${\underline {\mathbf {R} }}$ on any smooth manifold, so the sheaf cohomology of ${\underline {\mathbf {R} }}$ is equal to its de Rham cohomology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A different approach is by Čech cohomology. Čech cohomology was the first cohomology theory developed for sheaves and it is well-suited to concrete calculations, such as computing the coherent sheaf cohomology of complex projective space $\mathbb {P} ^{n}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It relates sections on open subsets of the space to cohomology classes on the space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In most cases, Čech cohomology computes the same cohomology groups as the derived functor cohomology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] However, for some pathological spaces, Čech cohomology will give the correct $H^{1}$ but incorrect higher cohomology groups.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] To get around this, Jean-Louis Verdier developed hypercoverings.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Hypercoverings not only give the correct higher cohomology groups but also allow the open subsets mentioned above to be replaced by certain morphisms from another space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This flexibility is necessary in some applications, such as the construction of Pierre Deligne's mixed Hodge structures.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Many other coherent sheaf cohomology groups are found using an embedding $i:X\hookrightarrow Y$ of a space X into a space with known cohomology, such as $\mathbb {P} ^{n}$ , or some weighted projective space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In this way, the known sheaf cohomology groups on these ambient spaces can be related to the sheaves $i_{*}{\mathcal {F}}$ , giving $H^{i}(Y,i_{*}{\mathcal {F}})\cong H^{i}(X,{\mathcal {F}})$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] For example, computing the coherent sheaf cohomology of projective plane curves is easily found.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] One big theorem in this space is the Hodge decomposition found using a spectral sequence associated to sheaf cohomology groups, proved by Deligne.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] the sheaf cohomology of a smooth projective variety X , degenerates, meaning $E_{1}=E_{\infty }$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This gives the canonical Hodge structure on the cohomology groups $H^{k}(X,\mathbb {C} )$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] It was later found these cohomology groups can be easily explicitly computed using Griffiths residues.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] These kinds of theorems lead to one of the deepest theorems about the cohomology of algebraic varieties, the decomposition theorem, paving the path for Mixed Hodge modules.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Another clean approach to the computation of some cohomology groups is the Borel–Bott–Weil theorem, which identifies the cohomology groups of some line bundles on flag manifolds with irreducible representations of Lie groups.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This theorem can be used, for example, to easily compute the cohomology groups of all line bundles on projective space and grassmann manifolds.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In many cases there is a duality theory for sheaves that generalizes Poincaré duality.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] See Grothendieck duality and Verdier duality.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This latter functor encompasses the notion of sheaf cohomology since $H^{n}(X,{\mathcal {F}})=R^{n}f_{*}{\mathcal {F}}$ for $f:X\to \{*\}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Like $f_{*}$ , the direct image with compact support $f_{!}$ can also be derived.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] By virtue of the following isomorphism $Rf_{!}{\mathcal {F}}$ parametrizes the cohomology with compact support of the fibers of f : $(R^{i}f_{!}{\mathcal {F}})_{y}=H_{c}^{i}(f^{-1}(y),{\mathcal {F}}).$ This isomorphism is an example of a base change theorem.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] In the context of quasi-coherent sheaves on schemes, there is a similar duality known as coherent duality.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Perverse sheaves are certain objects in $D(X)$ , i.e., complexes of sheaves (but not in general sheaves proper).
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] They are an important tool to study the geometry of singularities.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Another important application of derived categories of sheaves is with the derived category of coherent sheaves on a scheme X denoted $D_{Coh}(X)$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] where ${\mathcal {O}}_{Y_{i}}$ are coherent sheaves defined by the ${\mathcal {O}}_{X}$ -modules given by their structure sheaves.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] André Weil's Weil conjectures stated that there was a cohomology theory for algebraic varieties over finite fields that would give an analogue of the Riemann hypothesis.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The cohomology of a complex manifold can be defined as the sheaf cohomology of the locally constant sheaf ${\underline {\mathbf {C} }}$ in the Euclidean topology, which suggests defining a Weil cohomology theory in positive characteristic as the sheaf cohomology of a constant sheaf.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] But the only classical topology on such a variety is the Zariski topology, and the Zariski topology has very few open sets, so few that the cohomology of any Zariski-constant sheaf on an irreducible variety vanishes (except in degree zero).
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Alexandre Grothendieck solved this problem by introducing Grothendieck topologies, which axiomatize the notion of *covering*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Grothendieck's insight was that the definition of a sheaf depends only on the open sets of a topological space, not on the individual points.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] Once he had axiomatized the notion of covering, open sets could be replaced by other objects.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A presheaf takes each one of these objects to data, just as before, and a sheaf is a presheaf that satisfies the gluing axiom with respect to our new notion of covering.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] This allowed Grothendieck to define étale cohomology and ℓ-adic cohomology, which eventually were used to prove the Weil conjectures.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A category with a Grothendieck topology is called a *site*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] A category of sheaves on a site is called a *topos* or a *Grothendieck topos*.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p01] The notion of a topos was later abstracted by William Lawvere and Miles Tierney to define an elementary topos, which has connections to mathematical logic.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p02] The first origins of sheaf theory are hard to pin down; they may be co-extensive with the idea of analytic continuation.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p02] It took about 15 years for a recognisable, free-standing theory of sheaves to emerge from the foundational work on cohomology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p02] At this point sheaves had become a mainstream part of mathematics, with use by no means restricted to algebraic topology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/sheaf-mathematics-p02] It was later discovered that the logic in categories of sheaves is intuitionistic logic (this observation is now often referred to as Kripke–Joyal semantics, but probably should be attributed to a number of authors).
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] In algebraic geometry and commutative algebra, the **Zariski topology** is a topology defined on geometric objects called varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] It is very different from topologies that are commonly used in real or complex analysis; in particular, it is not Hausdorff.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] This topology was introduced primarily by Oscar Zariski and later generalized for making the set of prime ideals of a commutative ring (called the spectrum of the ring) a topological space.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] The Zariski topology allows tools from topology to be used to study algebraic varieties, even when the underlying field is not a topological field.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] This is one of the basic ideas of scheme theory, which allows one to build general algebraic varieties by gluing together affine varieties in a way similar to that in manifold theory, where manifolds are built by gluing together charts, which are open subsets of real affine spaces.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] The Zariski topology of an algebraic variety is the topology whose closed sets are the algebraic subsets of the variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] In the case of an algebraic variety over the complex numbers, the Zariski topology is thus coarser than the usual topology, as every algebraic set is closed for the usual topology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] This suggests defining the Zariski topology on the set of the maximal ideals of a commutative ring as the topology such that a set of maximal ideals is closed if and only if it is the set of all maximal ideals that contain a given ideal.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] Another basic idea of Grothendieck's scheme theory is to consider as *points*, not only the usual points corresponding to maximal ideals, but also all (irreducible) algebraic varieties, which correspond to prime ideals.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] Thus the Zariski topology on the set of prime ideals (spectrum) of a commutative ring is the topology such that a set of prime ideals is closed if and only if it is the set of all prime ideals that contain a fixed ideal.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] In classical algebraic geometry (that is, the part of algebraic geometry in which one does not use schemes, which were introduced by Grothendieck around 1960), the Zariski topology is defined on algebraic varieties.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] The Zariski topology, defined on the points of the variety, is the topology such that the closed sets are the algebraic subsets of the variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] As the most elementary algebraic varieties are affine and projective varieties, it is useful to make this definition more explicit in both cases.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] We assume that we are working over a fixed, algebraically closed field *k* (in classical algebraic geometry, *k* is usually the field of complex numbers).
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] First, we define the topology on the affine space $\mathbb {A} ^{n}$ , formed by the n -tuples of elements of k .
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] The topology is defined by specifying its closed sets, rather than its open sets, and these are taken simply to be all the algebraic sets in $\mathbb {A} ^{n}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] That is, the closed sets are those of the form $V(S)=\{x\in \mathbb {A} ^{n}\mid f(x)=0,\quad \forall f\in S\}$ where S is any set of polynomials in n variables over k .
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] It follows that finite unions and arbitrary intersections of the sets $V(S)$ are also of this form, so that these sets form the closed sets of a topology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] Writing $V(f)=V((f))$ , the sets $D(f)=\mathbb {A} ^{n}\setminus V(f)$ are open sets, known as the *principal* (or *distinguished*) *open sets*, that form a base for the topology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] This is the Zariski topology on $\mathbb {A} ^{n}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] If X is an affine algebraic set (irreducible or not) then the Zariski topology on it is defined simply to be the subspace topology induced by its inclusion into some $\mathbb {A} ^{n}$ .
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] This establishes that the above equation, clearly a generalization of the definition of the closed sets in $\mathbb {A} ^{n}$ above, defines the Zariski topology on any affine variety.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] Recall that n -dimensional projective space $\mathbb {P} ^{n}$ is defined to be the set of equivalence classes of non-zero points in $\mathbb {A} ^{n+1}$ by identifying two points that differ by a scalar multiple in k .
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] The projective Zariski topology is defined for projective algebraic sets just as the affine one is defined for affine algebraic sets, by taking the subspace topology.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] Similarly, it may be shown that this topology is defined intrinsically by sets of elements of the projective coordinate ring, by the same formula as above.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] The open sets in this base are called *distinguished* or *basic* open sets.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] The importance of this property results in particular from its use in the definition of an affine scheme.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] By Hilbert's basis theorem and the fact that Noetherian rings are closed under quotients, every affine or projective coordinate ring is Noetherian.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] As a consequence, affine or projective spaces with the Zariski topology are Noetherian topological spaces, which implies that any closed subset of these spaces is compact.
[src:algebraic-geometry/zariski-topology] However, except for finite algebraic sets, no algebraic set is ever a Hausdorff space.
